<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Water Project Inaugurated Near Ethiopia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- An emergency Dire dam
project, which cost 31 million U.S. dollars, was officially
inaugurated by head of Addis Ababa administration Ali Adbo on
Saturday, according to the Ethiopian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Dire Dam, located some 37 km north of Addis Ababa, is the
first largest drinking water dam built for the capital city of 2.3
million residents.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inaugural ceremony, the general manager of
Addis Ababa water and sewerage authority, Tadesse Kebede said the
city has been getting 30,000 cubic meters of water daily since the
project began operation three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
He said the city now meets 76 percent of the water demand as
against 60 percent previously.
</P>
<P>
The project started in 1996 and completed last December. About
12.5 million cubic meters of water has already been reserved in
the dam. When the level of the water reached to the dam's full
capacity, the city will get 12,000 cubic meters of additional
water daily.
</P>
<P>
This is one of two emergency water projects built for the city.
The Akaki emergency ground water project, built at a cost of 25
million U.S. dollars, will be completed at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Tadesse said when the Akaki project is completed the city could
be able to meet 95 percent of its water demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
