<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Reaches Compromise on New Strategy, U.N. Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) reached a compromise on a new strategy for the
21st century at its summit meeting Saturday, stressing the
preeminent responsibility of the United Nations for world peace.
</P>
<P>
The NATO draft agreement contained "satisfactory formulas for a
solution" for France, which advocates the role of the U.N.
Security Council in authorizing the use of force, French
presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said the compromise reaffirms "the authority of
the U.N. Security Council and its primordial responsibility" for
upholding international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The debate over NATO's new strategic concept, its key strategy
document, has dogged the alliance for the last six months.
</P>
<P>
Another compromise formula stipulates that NATO will operate in
the "Euro-Atlantic area," making clear the 19-nation Western
alliance does not see itself as a "world policeman."
</P>
<P>
The document on enlargement of NATO names all the Central and
East European countries aspiring to follow Poland, the Czech
Republic and Hungary in joining the alliance and offers them
individual Membership Action Plans to prepare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
