<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy in Zimbabwe to Continue Peace Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. special envoy for the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) Moustapha Niasse Saturday said
he had come to Harare to continue the mission of consultations at
different levels with all concerned parties in the DRC conflict.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released after a meeting with Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe, Niasse said during the course of this
month he had already met Secretary-General of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim in Addis Ababa, Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba has been mandated by the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) to lead the peace negotiations in the DRC war.
</P>
<P>
Niasse had also met with DRC President Laurent Kabila, Kenyan
President Daniel arap Moi and Burundi President Major Pierre
Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
Details of his deliberations were not revealed to the media but
 sources say the two touched on the recent libyan brokered
cease-fire agreement signed by Presidents Kabila, Yoweri Museveni
of Uganda, Idriss Deby of Chad and Muamar Gadaffi of Libya.
</P>
<P>
Niasse said his delegation would continue to emphasize the
willingness of the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, that of the
U.N. Security Council and the international community to the SADC
peace initiative led by President Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
"We will also strive to create new opportunities for the
attainment of peace, harmony, security and regional cooperation in
the spirit of resolution 1234 adopted by the Security Council in
New York on April 9," Niasse said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Security Council resolution 1234, among other things,
demands that all forces who are not in consistency with the
principles and purposes of the U.N. Charter pull out of the DRC
with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy arrived in Harare Friday and is expected to
leave Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
