<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Bangladesh Gets No Aid Commitments This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Much to its disappointment,
Bangladesh did not get any definitive commitments to the country's
request for 2.04 billion U.S. dollars in aid at the Bangladesh
Development Forum this year.
</P>
<P>
Shunning a direct answer whether donors had made any
commitments of aid at the two-day forum held in Paris on Monday
and Tuesday, Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria told reporters on
Saturday the "donors found the country's projection (of 2.04
billion dollars' aid) is realistic."
</P>
<P>
According to Kibria, the donors' aid flow would be more in the
next fiscal year (beginning July 1, 1999) than the amount sought
at the Paris meet, previously known as the Bangladesh Aid Group
Meeting, if utilization could be increased and on-going financial
reforms accelerated.
</P>
<P>
Unlike previous years, the donors refrained from making aid
commitments, as it had done in the past, which may indicate a
change in their policies towards aid to Bangladesh, observers here
said.
</P>
<P>
As a development forum, it focused on "development outcomes
rather than aid inputs," and the partners were moving away from
the previous format toward a genuine development forum in which
they were able to discuss ways of increasing the development
effectiveness of their investments ... in Bangladesh," a World
Bank press release said.
</P>
<P>
Other factors that may have prevented Bangladesh from getting
the anticipated aid pledge included an unstable political
situation, the slow pace of reforms, and the deteriorating law and
order situation in the country, the observers said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the country's donors raised their concern
over the political conflict in Bangladesh, and asked for a
resolution between the government and the opposition, but to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
"We've advised them (the donors) not to talk politics any
more... not to be worried about the political situation. We
assured them it will not affect foreign-aided development
projects," Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed
reportedly said early this month.
</P>
<P>
And even Kibria admitted that the donors were "not fully happy"
over the pace of reforms in Bangladesh and they suggested
accelerating the reforms, particularly in the banking and
financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
The partners said the development effectiveness of aid in
Bangladesh was dependent on good governance and urged the country
to speed up the process of decentralization, reduce corruption,
and improve further the law and order situation.
</P>
<P>
They were also concerned about the "lack of appreciable
results" in increasing the rate of cash recovery from the stock of
non-performing loans, raising the rate of resolution of pending
cases in the money loan courts, and reducing the intermediation
costs in banking, "indicating that the pillars of governance and
discipline had not yet been adequately rebuilt."
</P>
<P>
Observers said that lack of definitive aid pledges from donors
was a heavy blow to the already weak economy of Bangladesh, which
has about 50 percent of its annual development program fund from
external sources.
</P>
<P>
Without the aid commitments, the government would have a hard
time in drafting its budget for the coming fiscal year, they
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
