<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Seeks Foreign Assistance in Oil Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's Oil Minister
Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah reiterated Saturday that his country
needs technical assistance from international oil companies in
developing its oil potentials.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the National Assembly (Parliament) about the "Kuwait
oil project", Sheikh Saud stressed the project was aimed at
obtaining operational services from foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
He added that obtaining foreign technical expertise could
prolong the projected age of the oil fields and traps.
</P>
<P>
"Current trend of the petroleum industry focuses on principle
of cooperation with the international oil companies as a
method of work in exploration, production and phases of
manufacturing," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Saud said Kuwait has not signed any agreement or made
promises to any foreign companies in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, a Gulf state with a crude reserve of nearly 100
billion barrels, began to ponder the idea of seeking foreign
expertise in developing its oil fields in 1993.
</P>
<P>
State decision-makers have ever since been trying to map
out an appropriate form of getting foreign technical assistance
without affecting the state's ownership of its oil fields.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's constitution stipulates that foreign companies have no
right to own or utilize its natural wealth.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Kuwait has contacted several world oil majors,
including the U.S. Chevron Corp., on its oil development project.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf emirate was planning to invite foreign companies to
participate in the upstream operations in developing the oil
fields in the country's northern and western areas.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saud said last February that inviting foreign
participation in the upstream operations, which involve
exploration, development and production, would drastically boost
Kuwait's ability to face future challenges, increase Kuwait's oil
output and safeguard its interests.
</P>
<P>
By seeking foreign assistance, he added, Kuwait can witness the
introduction of high technology it does not possess, secure markets
to absorb Kuwaiti oil as well as win foreign capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
