<HEADLINE> Macedonia Closes Border with Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Macedonia closed its border with
Greece Friday to prevent any further NATO troops from entering the
country from Greece, an Albanian newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper "Gazeta Shaiptare" said that Macedonia, in which
12,000 NATO peacekeepers are deployed, does not want its territory
to be used to launch a ground offensive against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that NATO plans to send 2,000 German troops and
2,000 British troops via the Greek port of Selanik to reinforce
the peacekeepers in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia has long been resisting NATO's efforts in persuading
it to allow NATO forces to launch ground attacks on Serb soldiers
in Kosovo, which has been under extensive NATO air strikes since
March 24.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, Macedonian Foreign Minister Aleksandar Dimitrov
made an exchange of letters with NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana to regulate the mandate, stay and activities of the NATO
forces in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
A Macedonian news agency MIA report, which was monitored here,
said that both sides agreed the safety of all NATO member
countries is immediately connected with that of NATO partner
countries.
</P>
<P>
It was once again reaffirmed by the exchange of letters that
the territorial integrity, political independence and the security
of Macedonia will be respected and guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a Macedonian Information Ministry source as
saying that it was made clear again the NATO forces stationed in
Macedonia are not offensive.
</P>
<P>
On the sideline of the NATO Summit in Washington to mark the
50th birthday of the Western military organization, Dimitrov
Thursday attended a meeting organized by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeline Albright.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by officials from Yugoslavia's
neighboring countries, including Albania, Bulgaria, Romania,
Hungary, Bosnia, Croatia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
A number of initiatives for "transforming the Balkans and the
Southeastern Europe into a region of peace, security, economic
progress and democracy" were discussed at the meeting, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration presented its plans for "further
actions" in the Balkan region and additional humanitarian,
economic and financial aid to the countries affected by the Kosovo
crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
