<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Notifies U.N. of U.S., British Violation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has notified the U.N. of
violations of its airspace by the U.S. and British warplanes which
dropped fuel containers on some areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
In two letters addressed to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and U.N. Security Council, Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed
al-Sahhaf said that the aggressions by the U.S. and Britain had
led to the killing of a number of civilians, the Iraqi News Agency
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases dropped
fuel containers in the southern Iraqi province of Qadissiya, which
inflicted heavy damages, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The recurrent military attacks on Iraq were aimed at achieving
their political goals of undermining Iraq's sovereignty,
independence and territorial integrity, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since U.S. and Britain launched airstrikes on Iraq in
mid-December, their warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi
military sites and civilian facilities in the two no-fly zones in
the north and south of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"This aggressive act against Iraq and its people constitutes a
clear-cut breaching of the international law, and should not be
ignored or set aside by the Security Council and the U.N.,
especially when those who committed this hostile act are Security
Council permanent members," said Sahhaf.
</P>
<P>
In the letters, Sahhaf said that Iraq retained its full right
to adopt necessary measures to defend its sovereignty,
territorial integrity and security and to demand compensation for
the damages and casualties caused by the aggressions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq would strongly resist the so-called no-fly zones imposed
unilaterally by the U.S. and Britain after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in the
wake of the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppression." 
</P>
</TEXT>
