<HEADLINE> Saudi Crown Prince Meets With French Oilman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Crown Prince and
Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz met in the Saudi
summer capital of Jeddah Saturday with General Manager of the
French Total oil company Theri Demaris on prospects of
investment in the kingdom's energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed draft plans presented by Total in
response to an invitation made earlier by the Saudi crown
prince on world oil majors to invest in the Gulf country,
the Saudi Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Oil experts said that Riyadh was conducting in-depth studies
on plans proposed by international oil companies to choose the
most appropriate schemes.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen chief executives of foreign oil companies,
mostly American, have visited Saudi Arabia since Abdullah made
the call during his seven-nation global tour last September.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world largest oil producer, had been
reluctant to allow foreign participation in its oil and gas
exploration and production because of its current surplus output
capacity over 2 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources in the region said recent visits by
foreign oilmen and their meetings with Saudi senior officials
might have marked a shift in Riyahd's previous policy on
foreign investment in its energy sector. 
</P>
