<HEADLINE> Argentina Supports Egypt's Anti-Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Argentine Interior
Minister Carlos Corach on Saturday voiced his country's support
for Egypt's call for an international conference on combating
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Corach stressed that such a conference is helpful to curb
terrorism, which he said "has no boundaries and does not
differentiate between one state and the other."
</P>
<P>
The Argentine minister made the remarks during a meeting with
his Egyptian counterpart Habib Ibrahim el-Adli, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been a victim of terrorism carried out by Islamic
militants since 1992 in an attempt to topple the country's secular
government and install a strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
Cairo accused some countries of harboring terrorists and called
for an international conference under the auspices of the United
Nations to seek unified action against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Corach also voiced his country's readiness
to enhance cooperation with Egypt in the field of security.
</P>
<P>
The two officials reviewed bilateral cooperation in security
sphere and ways of fostering the relations, especially in the
confrontation of the organized crime, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Corach, who arrived in Cairo on Friday for a three-day visit,
said that his current trip mirrors the close ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Argentina signed an agreement on security cooperation
last May on the sidelines of a conference of the Group-15 held
here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
