<HEADLINE> African Leaders, U.S. Firms to Start Trade Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, United States, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A five-day
conference between African leaders and U.S. deal makers is
scheduled to begin here on Saturday afternoon to explore
opportunities for two-way trade and investment between Africa and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Organizers are finishing the final touch on the preparation for
the biannual conference, which is expect to draw five heads of state,
four prime ministers and high-level representatives of more than 26
African countries, senior U.S. government officials and
entrepreneurs as well as the chief executive officials of some of
America's largest corporations.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Festus Mongae of Botswana, Omar Bongo of Gabon, Jerry
Rawlings of Ghana, Sam Nujoma of Namibia and Teodoro Obiang Nguema
Mbasogo of Equitorial Guinea are expected to be present at the summit,
organizing officials said.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers of Cote d'Ivoire, Mali, Mauritius and Niger
as well as the vice-president-elect will also attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
Other African participants will include ministers or senior
government representatives from Algeria, Angola, Benin, Burkina
Faso, Burundi, Cameroon, Cape Verde, Central African Republic,
Congo, Djibouti, Egypt, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Sierra
Leone, South Africa, Togo, Zambia and Zimbabwe, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the upcoming meeting is Thema Awori, director of
the African Bureau of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP),
which will sponsor a workshop on "Financial Intermediation and
Private Sector in Africa" at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The gathering, titled "Attracting Capital to Africa Summit," is
aimed at helping create joint ventures between U.S. and African
companies, encouraging U.S. investment in Africa and highlighting
investment opportunities on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Top U.S. government officials expected at the conference include
the secretaries of commerce, energy, transportation.
</P>
<P>
On April 21, 1997, some 700 people gathered at Chantilly,
Virginia, to participate in a summit to attract American business to
Africa and to celebrate the economic renaissance of African
continent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
