<HEADLINE> First Libyan Airliner Lands at Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A Libyan airliner, the first
after the U.N. suspension of air embargo earlier this month,
landed at Damascus International Airport Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On board of the Libyan Plane was Mohammed Abou Gharis,
Director General of the Libyan Civil Aviation Authority, a number
of Libyan transport officials together with a galaxy of artists
and some Libyan folklore troupes which gave a series of popular
local performances at the welcoming ceremony held to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian national carrier was also the first airlines company
to fly a plane to Libya on April 10 after the U.N. sanctions
imposed on this North African country was suspended.
</P>
<P>
Libya had been under U.N. sanctions since 1992 for its refusal
to hand over two suspects in the bombing of a Pan-American
airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyan suspects were handed over to the U.N. on April 5
to be tried in the Netherlands before a Scottish court. In return,
the U.N. sanctions against Libya was automatically suspended and
will be lifted within 90 days after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan submits a report to the Security Council, stating that Libya
has complied with all relevant resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
