<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Rejects NATO Presence in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia would not allow
any presence of armed foreign troops on territory to enforce a
possible peace agreement in Kosovo, Belgrade's Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic said in an interview with the Washington Post
published on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Such a peacekeeping force would contradict Yugoslavia's
"sovereignty and territorial integrity," and any ground invasion
of Yugoslavia would widen the conflict "beyond the borders of
Yugoslavia" and pose "dangers to the whole continent," Jovanovic
said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also warned a NATO ground invasion of
Kosovo -- a possibility that is increasingly under consideration
-- would widen the present war "beyond the borders of Yugoslavia"
and pose dangers to the whole continent."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam "would be nothing" compared with the kind of war the
United States would risk in Yugoslavia, he said. "We are ready to
defend our country and we shall succeed," he added.
</P>
<P>
A NATO ground campaign "would be yet another miscalculation by
those who have already been proved wrong so far," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic spoke with the Washington Post in his office at the
Foreign Ministry shortly before NATO issued a statement on
Kosovo at its Washington summit.
</P>
<P>
He said Belgrade was prepared to accept the return of ethnic
Albanian refugees to Kosovo under the supervision of an
international force, but such a force could not be armed and
could not include representatives of the United States and other
countries "involved in aggression against Yugoslavia." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
