<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese government is considering selling off
two-thirds of Lebanon's national flag carrier the Middle East
Airlines (MEA) to the private sector, the Arabic daily Al-Hayat
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Minister of Public Works and Transportation Najib
Mikati told the paper that the government might sell off
two-thirds of the financially-troubled airline to foreign
partners, while holding the remaining one third to monitor the
parters.
</P>
<P>
The move is intended to rescue MEA from a burden of debts
amounting to 234 million U.S. dollars accrued in the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister refused to give a price tag for the deal,
maintaining that it could go up if MEA retrieves its financial
losses and undergoes further rehabilitation, attracting better
offers.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- The Arab Fund for Economic and Social Development (AFESD)
has agreed to provide Yemen with a loan of 58 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deal was concluded in Doha Saturday on the sidelines of a
meeting of 20 Arab finance ministers and 11 Central Bank
governors, the Egyptian Arabic daily Al-Alam Alyoum reported.
</P>
<P>
The loan, at an interest rate of 4.5 percent, is to be paid
back in 20 years with a grace period of four years.
</P>
<P>
The money is to be used financing a project on drainage water
recycling and disposal in the Yemeni capital of Sanaa.
</P>
<P>
The Doha-based AFESD is an Arab League financial agency
established in 1974 to extend long-term loans and technological
assistance to Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Yemen has received about 780 million U.S. dollars of loans from
the Fund so far.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
predicted that the value of the projects to be carried out in the
Palestinian territories of the West Bank and Gaza Strip by the end
of this year would reach 300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al Haiyat Saturday quoted a recently-released
U.N. report as saying that the UNDP has spent 284 million dollars
in infrastructure, agricultural, health, tourism and housing
schemes in the territories over a 20-year period.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Over 15 percent of Iran's foodstaffs are imported and
currently there is a deficit of 2 billion U.S. dollars in the
sector's trade balance, Iranian Agriculture Minister Issa
Kalantari said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran's foodstuffs exports stood at 1 billion
dollars while imports at 3 billion dollars, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture sector holds the biggest share in the country's
gross domestic product with 27 percent and Iran's farm products
reached over 63 million tons in the past Iranian year ended on
March 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
