<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Renews Cease-fire in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
agreed to renew an interim cease-fire in southern Sudan to
facilitate humanitarian aid to reach the needy in the south.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Relations Saturday said in a press
statement that the move would create adequate atmosphere for peace
negotiations between the government and the Southern People's
Liberation Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
The government, in renewing the ceasefire in the southern Bahr
al-Ghazal province, expressed hope that the ongoing consultations
would result in a comprehensive cease-fire to pave the way for
peaceful and smooth flow of humanitarian aid to southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Head of the Southern States Co-ordination Committee
Riak Mashar accused the SPLA of not responding to the peaceful
efforts of the government.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA, as one of Sudan's leading opposition groups, was
unwilling to conclude a peace deal with the Sudanese government,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Civil war broke out between southern rebels and the government
in the north in 1983 and more than 1.9 million people have died in
fighting and war-related famines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
