<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian-African Legal Committee to work with U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (xINHUA) -- Participants at the 38th Session
of the Asian-African Consultative Committee (AALCC) meeting which
ended in Accra Saturday have resolved to cooperate with the U.N.
and other international bodies to ensure peace and the alleviation
of poverty, the Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution, they commended efforts to find a solution to
the Middle East crisis based on U.N. Security Council resolutions
on "land for peace" and legitimate rights of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
 "Mindful of the difficulties being faced in the
implementation of peace process, AALCC expresses hope that a just
and durable solution will allow the Palestinian people to attain
their legitimate rights," the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
 They took note of the difficulties migrant workers face and
the need to protect their basic human rights and requested its
secretariat to convene an "Open Ended Working Group" to consider
the issue.
</P>
<P>
 The session recognized the importance of consultations
between member states on the status and treatment of Refugees and
asked member states to submit comments on the matter relating to
Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Committee requested its secretary-general to make further
consultations with member states and the Office of the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, to finalize the text of
the revised Bangkok Principles on refugees.
</P>
<P>
 It urged member states to consider ratifying the statute on
the establishment of an International Criminal Court, which will
be open for signature at the U.N. headquarters from December 31,
2000.
</P>
<P>
The resolution acknowledged the growing importance of global
electronic. commerce and the expertise developed within the U.N.
and other international organizations concerned with international
trade law.
</P>
<P>
It therefore urged member states to consider adopting,
ratifying or acceding to the instruments prepared by the U.N.
Commission on International trade Law.
</P>
<P>
The AALCC resolved to encourage its member states to take
active interest in the deliberations of the World Trade
Organization, International Environmental Law and International
Law Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
