<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Asks Iraq to Clarify Fate of Iranian POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official on
Sunday called on Iraq to clarify the fate of 2,806 Iranian
Prisoners of War (POWs) held in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Abdollah Najafi, the head of the Iranian special commission in
charge of POWs, said the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) has confirmed the documents were provided by Iran on the
remaining POWs in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has offered a list on the Iranian POWs in Iraq and
promised to help secure their release, Najafi was quoted by the
Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the Iraqi side will follow up the case
and the Iranian POWs still being held in Iraq will be granted
freedom soon.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has also claimed that about 2,000 Iraqi POWs are still
being held in Iran, Najafi said. But he neither confirmed nor
rejected the Iraqi claim.
</P>
<P>
He said 3,587 Iraqi POWs have refused to return to Iraq and
chosen to remain in Iran as refugees.
</P>
<P>
Iran released 6,246 Iraqi POWs unilaterally last year in
coordination with the ICRC while Iraq freed 372 Iranian POWs, the
Iranian official said.
</P>
<P>
Iran precisely examined a list of 9,162 Iraqi nationals
provided by Iraq, but many of the names were repetitive, exchanged
before, refugees or unknown to Iran, Najafi said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran determined the fate of 18,995 Iraqi POWs
last year.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq reached an agreement last June to settle the
issue of POWS, which has been preventing the two neighbors from
resuming normal relations since the end of their eight-year war in
1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
