<HEADLINE> Arafat Consults With Ghana on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
Sunday held talks with Ghanaian officials led by Vice-President
John Atta Mills on the Mid-East peace process with particular
focus on the intended declaration of statehood by Palestine, the
Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Ghanaian capital Accra Saturday night as part
of his African tour to seek advice on whether to go ahead with the
declaration or to delay the process till the Israeli elections
slated for May 17.
</P>
<P>
The 1993 Oslo Accord provides for the declaration of Palestine
as an independent state from May 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by his Minister of International Cooperation,
Nabeel Shaath and his political advisor, Nabeel Abourdene, Arafat
had been to Conakry, Guinea, and Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader told reporters on arrival that the
Palestinian authority has the right to declare independence.
</P>
<P>
However, consultations are necessary "with brothers and
friends" whose support Palestine has enjoyed over the years on the
subject, said Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Sampling views during his tour, he said, "some of them are
advising us to delay a little bit and make the declaration after
the Israeli elections."
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, a final decision will come from the Palestine
Central Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"I will discuss my findings from the consultations with the
Central Council before a final decision is taken," he said.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth visit to Ghana by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
In a pre-departure briefing, Shaath described the Accra talks
as extremely fruitful, saying that the outcome will be a major
input for consideration by the Palestine General Assembly when it
reconvenes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Ghana's role in the peace process is vital and
hopes the west African country would spearhead the international
campaign for a successful peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official commented on recent actions taken by
the Israeli government against Palestine's facilities, saying that
they could have very serious and negative repercussions on the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel recently closed the Palestinian office in east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to visit Nigeria and Ethiopia before
returning home.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings is currently on an official
tour to the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
