<HEADLINE> China's Investment in Ethnic Groups Grows Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's investment in minority
ethnic-group areas has been increasing rapidly over the past years,
according to Li Rongrong, vice minister of the State Development
and Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Reporting to the 7th meeting of the Nationalities Committee of
the 9th National People's Congress (NPC) today, Li said that among
the 2,656 infrastructure investment projects in China last year, 1,
750, or 66 percent, were in the central and western regions where
most of the country's ethnic-minority population lives, and 530 of
these projects, or 20 percent, were in other concentrated ethnic
areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, he said, China's average growth rate for investment
in state-owned units was 19.5 percent, while the figure was 75.4
percent in the Tibet Autonomous Region, 25.9 percent in the
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, and 22.2 percent in the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
He added that during the 1980-1998 period, the average GDP
growth rate for China's five ethnic autonomous regions, and among
the three provinces of Guizhou, Yunnan and Qinghai where ethnic
minorities live in compact communities, was 0.5 percentage points
higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly increased investment in infrastructure construction
in China's ethnic concentrated areas will greatly improve
transportation, flood control, electricity supply, and
environmental protection there, he said.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was presided over by Wang Chaowen, head of the
Nationalities Committee of the 9th NPC. Tomur Dawamat, vice
chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, was also present at
today's meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
