<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Vows to Cut Industrial Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- This largest commercial and
industrial center of China plans to reduce the proportion of its
money-losing state-owned and state-controlled enterprises from 35
percent to 15 percent by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
This plan means that some 400 money-losing state-owned
enterprises, and enterprises in which the state holds a
controlling interest, will be brought out of the red, according to
a municipal industry official.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai currently has more than 1,700 state-owned firms and 1,
000 state-controlled firms, and 35 percent of these enterprises
are now operating in the red, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's industrial economic efficiency improved last year
with a 10.8 percent increase in total industrial production and
profits reaching 20 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of this year, the profit volume among
Shanghai's industrial firms jumped 31.3 percent to 2.27 billion
yuan, while total losses of the money-losing firms dropped 16.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Currently, state-owned firms account for 22.8 percent of the
combined asset volume of all Shanghai industrial firms, down 6.3
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The official said that losses have occurred as a result of
unreasonable product mix, declining prices, the interaction of the
forces of foreign exchange, tax and interest rates, a lack of
circulating funds, economic restructuring, and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Since the causes of the losses are clear, the objective of
significantly reducing the number of failing firms can be
accomplished as scheduled, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
