<HEADLINE> China Leads World in Deep-Reservoir Oil Exploiting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China has dug 527 oil wells each
at a depth of more than 4,500 meters at the Tarim Basin in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
These wells, scattered among eight of the 14 oil fields in
Tarim, have produced 20 million tons of crude oil, said Wang
Yiqing , deputy chief engineer of the Tarim Oil Prospecting and
Exploiting Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Emerging as China's eighth-largest crude oil and natural gas
producer, the Tarim Basin has potential oil reserves of over 10.7
billion tons, and natural gas reserves of over 8.4 trillion cubic
meters, accounting for about 13 percent and 25 percent of the
current total respectively, according to an official resource-
assessment report.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the oil resources in Tarim were buried 4,500
meters beneath the ground surface. In addition, many oil layers
are located between gas-bearing and water structures.
</P>
<P>
Many hi-tech capabilities including air-pumping and reservoir
description technology are employed in drilling the ultra-deep
wells in Tarim, said 59-year-old Wang, who has headed a technical
group in Tarim for many years.
</P>
<P>
Oil workers have also developed technology for drilling oil
wells in the desert, for drilling five horizontal wells at the
Tazhong Oil Field to develop oil layers of the carboniferous
system, each with a daily output of 1,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
