<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Urges to Solve Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
Sunday urged the Israeli government to solve the dispute over
Jerusalem through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, the top Palestinian official in Jerusalem,
told reporters at the Orient House in east Jerusalem that the
Israeli government's order to close the Orient House may cause
unrest in the holy city.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Israeli government led by Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has insisted on its position over the issue of
Jerusalem and claimed the city as the indivisible and eternal
capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the Palestinians also have the right to make
their position clear that they regard Jerusalem as the capital of
their future independent nation.
</P>
<P>
Husseini stressed that for this reason the dispute over
Jerusalem could be solved only through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's security cabinet ordered the closure of the
Palestinian National Authority's (PNA) offices in the Orient House
on Thursday, a day after Husseini invited European consuls to the
compound.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials have noted that the peace agreement signed
between Israel and the PNA ban Palestinian activities in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Husseini told reporters that the Orient House does not
represent the PNA, noting that the compound has been working as a
Palestinian center for years.
</P>
<P>
He also indicated that Netanyahu was seeking publicity ahead
of the May 17 elections by ordering the closure.
</P>
<P>
Husseini did not specify how the Palestinians will react if
the closure is implemented, but said the closure will make "a lot
of problems" in the city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian lawyer Jawad Boulos said on Friday that
he would appeal any closure orders to the Israeli Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
And legal experts quoted in Israeli newspapers said the
closure procedure would take at least two weeks and might be
stopped by the courts.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem from
Jordan in the 1967 Mideast war and later annexed it. The
Palestinians want to establish a future capital in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to the peace agreements signed by the two sides, the
issue of Jerusalem should be settled in the final status talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
