<HEADLINE> Rwandan Govt Slammed for Detaining Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan Association of
Journalists (ARJ) has strongly protested the illegal detention of
two journalists: John Eddie Mugabi and Amiel Nkuliza, the Rwanda
News Agency (RNA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a protest note addressed to President Pasteur Bizimungu on
Saturday asking for his intervention to help end harassment and
pressure on reporters in the country, ARJ condemned the arrest of
the two scribes.
</P>
<P>
''On the eve of May 3, the World Day on he Freedom of the
Press, we, members of the Association Rwandaise des Journalistes
(ARJ), do write to you Excellency, Pasteur Bizimungu, to protest
the arrest and detention of our members and colleagues,'' the note
said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabi, the News editor of the English monthly Newsline, and
Nkuliza, the "Directeur de Publication'' of Le Partisan were
respectively arrested on February 26, 1999, and May 14, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mugabi is reportedly kept in custody on grounds of alleged
defamation of the Secretary General in the Ministry of Defense,
Colonel Frank Rusagara, whom he said in a story about a helicopter
deal which ''might have obtained a 10 percent commission through
underhand methods.''
</P>
<P>
The ARJ recalled that ''at the beginning of the year, the
helicopter saga was reported several times in Ugandan press where
the story featured prominently.''
</P>
<P>
It is said that Mugabi accepted responsibility of being the
author of the story during the interrogation by the Kigali
prosecutor, Emmanual Rukangira, but refused to disclose the source
of his news story.
</P>
<P>
''On being pushed further, Mugabi told the prosecutor that he
can only reveal the source before the Court,'' underscored the
ARJ.
</P>
<P>
Mugabi was subsequently thrown into prison and well-informed
sources say that he is detained at Remera Central Prison, in the
outskirts of the capital, together with genocide suspects.
</P>
<P>
''We find this uncalled-for pressure to force journalists to
reveal the source of his news story unacceptable,'' the ARJ told
president Bizimungu.
</P>
<P>
''For a government official of Mr. Rukangira's standing, and a
highly placed senior lawyer at that, to subject a journalist to
pressure in order to reveal the source of his news story under
duress is nothing but a violation of basic freedoms of journalists
in this country,'' it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The ARJ stated that they protest against the detention of
Mugabi as a criminal, while his case is civil one.
</P>
<P>
But argued Rukangira, Mugabi's case is a penal one, and it was
filed by Rusagara as any individual who felt offended by the
journalist's alleged defamation.
</P>
<P>
'It is unbelievable for a civil case of alleged defamation or
libel, which has not been proved beyond reasonable doubt, to be
treated and handled as if it is a criminal one,'' ARJ stressed.
''At the time, the manner of his arrest was unfair, contestable
and unprocedural,'' observed the association.
</P>
<P>
The ARJ sees in Mugabi's case, the attempt by the government to
 intimidate and muffle the press which, in the past months, has
been very vitriolic about creeping corruption in the country, thus
triggering hostility in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
The Assumption by the ARJ stemmed from the fact that while
appearing before court on April 15, Mugabi was denied the release
on bail, because the prosecutor ''unfairly convinced the court to
deny him bail and insisted that he (Mugabi) should remain in
detention till the next hearing date.''
</P>
<P>
''We find this kind of prolonged detention contrary to the law,
indeed, a violation of Universal Law on Basic Human Rights and an
abuse to the liberties and freedoms of the press,'' highlighted
the ARJ.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the situation of Mugabi's family is precarious
because he was the sole bread winner before his arrest. He
reportedly left behind his wife an one day old baby, now faced
with a number of problems, starvation not withstanding.
</P>
<P>
''If we can report on some situations because they implicate
some members of the government, how is the media here going to
help redress the abuses of the past,'' one Kigali-based reporter
who asked not to be named told the Rwanda News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the case of Nkuliza remains a mystery, noted ARJ in
the note filed to Bizimungu. It is reported that there were at a
certain time allegations of involvement in the genocide, but this
changed into something else the association is not informed of.
</P>
<P>
''We believe that Mr Amiel is genuinely held under unclear
charges, which is yet another way of muzzling the press,''
observed the association.
</P>
<P>
The ARJ called for a partnership with the government in the
process of good governance and development.
</P>
<P>
Rukangira told RNA that he is no longer in charge of Mugabi's
case file, and directed the agency to seek explanation from a
judge at the Kigali Court of First Instance who is handling the
case.
</P>
<P>
The reaction of the government is yet to come, but already fear
among media practitioners has increased in face of alleged
harassment of the press which is seen as a big threat to its
rightful place in the rebuilding of genocide-torn Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
