<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Qatar has concluded a 400-million-U.S.-dollar loan with
14 banks for the establishment of a liquefied natural gas plant.
</P>
<P>
Yousef Hussein Kamal, minister of finance and economy and trade
and deputy chairman of the General Petroleum Establishment of
Qatar, said Saturday that the liquefied natural gas operations
assume an important position in Qatar's energy network.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Iraq is planning to increase its foreign currency
income through promoting religious tourism to the sacred shrines
in Karbalaa and Nejev.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi endeavour was expressed in the talks in Dubai between
aviation officials of Iraq and the United Arab Emirates over
launching tourism-oriented air lines between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Sudanese Minister of Finance and Economy Abdel-Wahab
Osman, said Sudan was seeking to re-schedule its
300-million-dollar debts to the International Monetary Fund, the
Arab Currency Fund and the Arab Fund for Economic and Social
Development.
</P>
<P>
He anticipated that a settlement of this issue would be reached
over the coming few months.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The Iraqi Central Bank will issue a new currency of
high face value in the near future, the Arab Photographer weekly
quoted Issam Hwaish, governor of the Iraqi Central Bank, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate on when the new currency will be issued
and what the new currency's face value will be. 
</P>
</TEXT>
