<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Steps up Anti-Taliban Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan opposition Sunday
reported new impetus in several northern provinces in a bid to
repel the Taliban armies since the capture of Bamyan city by the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the opposition Shiite Harakat-e-Islami Saad
Mohseni said in a message from Tashkent, capital of Tajikistan,
that Northern Alliance has intensified operation in Samangan,
Balkh, Faryab and Jawzjan provinces.
</P>
<P>
"Our commanders from Central Afghanistan have confirmed fierce
fighting in Kotal e Shebar, Kotal e Hajy Gak and Dara e Shekari,"
Mohseni said.
</P>
<P>
He said fighting has also flared up in Faryab following the
brief capture of Juma Bazaar by troops loyal to the alliance last
week.
</P>
<P>
Mohseni said that the much-publicized "mutiny" has been quelled
in Faizabad, capital of Badakhshan province.
</P>
<P>
The spring season in Afghanistan has begun with the fall of
Bamyan city to the anti-Taliban alliance, which is a big
achievement of the opposition after its defeats last year.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports that the Taliban, who controls more than
80 percent of the war-torn country, is regrouping and may launch a
big offensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
