<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vaccination to Block Spread of Hepatitis B in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese health officials today
called for enhanced efforts to vaccinate newborn babies against
hepatitis B, saying this is the most efficient and economical
method to curb this contagious disease.
</P>
<P>
They said that if vaccinations are given to all newborns from
now on, the ratio of HBV (hepatitis B virus) carriers in the
Chinese population will drop below one percent in 50 years from
the current 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of an over 90 percent vaccination rate among urban
babies, only some 30 percent in the vast rural areas are
vaccinated against hepatitis B, mainly due to ignorance or lack of
money to pay for vaccinations," an official at the Ministry of
Health said at an event to publicize vaccinations with the theme:
Expand the Hepatitis B Immunization Program (EPI) in China.
</P>
<P>
China has about 120 million HBV carriers, and 12 million suffer
from chronic liver illnesses, 300,000 of whom die each year. Most
cases are the result of hepatitis B and C infection, according to
experts at the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine (CAPM).
</P>
<P>
"About 40 percent of hepatitis B infections are mother-to-
infant cases. But the virus in babies can be stopped if they are
vaccinated 24 hours after birth," said Professor Su Chong'ao of
the CAPM.
</P>
<P>
However, the rate of the vaccination remains around 30 percent
in the country's rural and poor areas where two-thirds of the
nation's population lives.
</P>
<P>
"Many parents in these areas are unaware of the importance of
vaccination, or they just can't afford it," the MOH official said.
</P>
<P>
The government decided to include hepatitis B vaccination in
the national EPI program in 1992, but provided few funds for
nationwide free services such as vaccination against polio.
</P>
<P>
Health economists have warned that the country could suffer 30
to 50 billion yuan (or about 3.6 to 6 billion U.S. dollars) in
extra medical expenditures annually due to the spread of hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
Several charity campaigns have been launched across the country
to raise funds and vaccine donations. The Chinese Foundation for
Hepatitis Prevention and Control, for example, has received 3.5
million yuan and 710,000 units of hepatitis A and B vaccine since
it was set up earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine has been sent to areas hit by last summer's floods
and poverty-stricken regions including the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region and Gansu Province, according to the foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
