<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Economy to Grow 3.6 Pct This Year: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's economy is projected
to grow by about 3.6 percent in the current fiscal year ending
June 30, 1999, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The growth performance in recent years has been encouraging"
in Bangladesh, which "has been finally able to break the 4 percent
per annum growth barrier that existed in the 1970s and 80s,"
Phiphit Suphaphiphat, resident representative of the ADB, told
reporters while releasing the "Asian Development Outlook 1998."
</P>
<P>
The growth this year, however, was lower than last year's 5.7
percent, due to the impact of the devastating flood of 1998, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The outlook forecasts a 5.5 percent growth for the South Asian
nation in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
It expresses concern at the high fiscal deficit, deterioration
in the financial position of state-owned enterprises, the recent
stagnation in the government's revenue collection, inflationary
pressures in the economy, and the low and declining levels of
foreign exchange reserves in the country.
</P>
<P>
The outlook is also concerned with the slow-down in the pace of
reforms in 1998, and hopes the Bangladeshi government would
"accelerate the pace of economic reforms to pave the way for
sustained and rapid economic development."
</P>
<P>
Suphaphiphat confirmed at the press conference that the
country's donors did not make any aid pledge at the Bangladesh
Development Forum held in Paris on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The forum, previously known as the Paris Aid Consortium
meeting, had changed its format from a "aid-pledging session" to a
forum for discussing policy issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the donors would continue to provide assistance
to Bangladesh if the government kept its commitments to speeding
up reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
