<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- A day after deciding to intensify the fury of their bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia, North Atlantic Treaty Organization(
NATO) leaders approved a new strategic concept for the alliance
Saturday that for the first time embraces military missions in
volatile regions beyond their own borders.
</P>
<P>
-- As he prepares for the upcoming presidential campaign, U.S.
Texas Governor George W. Bush is a man determined to shed the hard-
edged ideology of the Republican Party but reluctant to move too
rapidly to the political center.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), South
Korea, China and the United States opened a new phase in their
peace talks in Geneva Saturday, beginning their first substantive
negotiations after more than a year of meetings to lay the
groundwork.
</P>
