<HEADLINE> NATO Bombings Hit Four Serbian Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Powerful bombings hit four
Serbian towns of Belgrade, Avala, Lucani and Nis on Sunday as NATO
air strikes against Yugoslavia entered the 33rd day.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia's official Tanjug news agency reported that NATO
bombings at 02:50 local time early Sunday destroyed a transformer
station at the foot of Avala mountains, 15 kilometers south of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Four missiles hit the northeastern industrial area of Nis, 200
kilometers southeast of Belgrade, causing "great damage," Tanjug
reported.
</P>
<P>
Five missiles also hit the chemical plant in Lucani about 100
kilometers south of the capital early Sunday in NATO's fourth
attack on the largest factory in the town.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique released on Sunday by the Kosovo News
Bureau, the Yugoslav forces on Saturday shot down three NATO
planes, but no details were given.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several thousand volunteers from Belgrade,
Montenegro, Bosnia, Greece, Macedonia, Ukraine, Russia, Italy and
some Arab countries continued to stand as "human shields" on three
bridges across the Sava and Danube rivers, chanting songs in
protest against NATO's raids on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Reports say that thousands of Belgraders are going to rally at
the central square in the Yugoslav capital at midday Saturday to
mourn for those killed by NATO bombings at the Serbian state radio
and television building early Friday. The Tanjug reported that at
least 10 people were killed and 18 injured in the attack. 
</P>
