<HEADLINE> Death Toll of Ugandan Capital Bomb Blast Rises to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of the bomb blast,
which took place in downtown Kampala Saturday evening, has reached
four as an old lady of 65 died in hospital Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Kyomukama James, a police officer of Uganda's Criminal
Investigations Department (CID), told Xinhua in Mulago hospital
here Sunday morning that the newly dead is Woman Special Constable
Hajati Masitula.
</P>
<P>
Conditions of the remaining 13 people injured in the explosion
are stable and improving, he said.
</P>
<P>
The blast, which happened behind the Nakivubo Stadium at around
8:00 p.m. (local time), occurred minutes after a policeman was
shot dead in the same area.
</P>
<P>
Many people rushed to see what had happened to the policeman
when the terrorist threw the bomb into the crowd, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kyomukama said there has been no arrest so far and that it is
still too early for him to comment on the motive of the incident.
</P>
<P>
Ogwal Charles, a police officer attached to Old Kampala police
station who sustained knee and hand injuries in the blast, told
Xinhua in the hospital that the street is one of the busiest in
the capital city and that a local football match was going on in
the stadium before the blast.
</P>
<P>
When asked if more policemen will be deployed in the area
following two bomb blasts in the area two weeks ago, he said that
there is no reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism-related bombing is a new phenomenon in Uganda and so
far more than 50 people have been killed during blasts of this
nature since 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
