<HEADLINE> Appeal of Former PM's Assassin's Friend Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Tel Aviv District Court
rejected on Sunday Margalit Har-Shefi's appeal that she was not
responsible for the assassination of former Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Three judges of the court passed their ruling with two to one,
maintaining that Har-Shefi was involved in the assassination by
failing to take reasonable steps to prevent the murder.
</P>
<P>
Her friend, Yigal Amir, killed Rabin with a hand gun on
November 4, 1995. He was sentenced to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The ruling said that Har-Shefi, a law student of Bar-Illan
University from the West Bank settlement of Beit El, has to serve
nine months in prison passed on her by the Tel Aviv Magistrate
Court last September.
</P>
<P>
She told the police after Rabin's assassination that Amir had
told her about the assassination plan, but she did not inform the
police of that.
</P>
<P>
The Tel Aviv Magistrate Court ruled last June that Har-Shefi
was partially responsible for the murder because if she had tipped
off to the police, the assassination could have been avoided.
</P>
<P>
The Magistrate Court sentenced her to nine months in prison
last September and a 15-month suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
Her-Shefi filed her appeal to the Tel Aviv District Court,
hoping to overturn the Magistrate Court's verdict.
</P>
<P>
Amir, a right wing activist, is now serving his prison terms at
Beer Sheba Jail in south Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
