<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq: International Support for Lifting Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Iraq's National
Assembly (parliament) Saadoun Hammadi said on Sunday that
international support for Iraq's demand for lifting U.N. sanctions
is mounting up.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Iraqi News Agency, Hammadi, who had led
an Iraqi delegation to the International Parliamentary Federation
Conference which concluded lately in Brussels, said participates
of the conference called for lifting the sanctions and denounced
the on-going U.S-British air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed sweeping economic sanctions on Iraq
following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait which touched off the 1991
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi said the Iraqi delegation had meetings with a number of
foreign parliamentary delegations on the sidelines of the
conference and discussed the current situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain launched four nights of
airstrikes against Iraq last December to retaliate what they
called Iraq's failure to fully cooperate with U.N. weapons
inspectors in charge of eliminating Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
After the bombardment, Iraq declared it does not recognize the
two no-fly zones imposed by the U.S. and Britain after the Gulf
War, and vowed to fire at any allied warplanes violating its
airspace.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. and Britain said they were determined to
enforce the restricted zones, set up allegely to protect the Kurds
in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south of Iraq from
"Baghdad's repression."
</P>
<P>
The allied warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi
targets in the no-fly zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
