<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hostages Released, But Disputes Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippines' New People's Army
(NPA) released Sunday its last government captive for the
resumption of the peace talks between the NPA and the government,
but some disputes concerning the peace talks have to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Saturday, Philippine President Joseph Estrada said
that his government will immediately resume the peace talks with
National Democratic Front (NDF), the political arm of NPA, once
the latter releases Sgt. Wivino Demol whom it abducted on February
9, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The formal peace talks between the government and the NPA
suspended on Feb. 22 following the abduction by the NPA of Brig.
Gen. Victor Obillo and Capt. Eduardo Montealto on Feb.17.
</P>
<P>
Later the NPA also abducted police Chief Inspector Roberto
Bernal and Sgt. Alipio Lozada, on Feb. 22 and March 5
respectively.
</P>
<P>
An independent third-party group led by Davao Archbishop
Fernando Capalla negotiated for the release of the five government
hostages in the Netherlands on March 16 and 17. NDF leaders
finally promised to release the hostages on the condition that
government troops suspend offensive military operations in the
concerned area to facilitate the release.
</P>
<P>
NPA released Obillo and three other captives from April 9 to
16, but failed to release Demol by the deadline of April 19,
quoting the offensive operations launched by the government troops
as the reason.
</P>
<P>
Both the Philippine government and NPA have expressed their
hope to resume peace talks as soon as possible, but some disputes
about the peace talks have not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada has stressed once and again that the formal
peace talks only take place in the Philippines, but NDF repeatedly
calls on the government to hold the peace talks in the
Netherlands, the present home base of self-exiled NDF founding
chairman Jose Ma. Sison.
</P>
<P>
"Why settle the problem in another country? If they want to
have peace, they should work for it here in the Philippines. I
will not allow any government official to conduct peace talks
with them abroad," Estrada once said.
</P>
<P>
The president also questioned the qualification of Luis
Jalandoni, chairman of the NDF peace panel to speak on behalf of
the NDF, saying Jalandoni is no longer a Filipino after he changed
his citizenship to Dutch.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Estrada set the end of this year as the deadline
for the government and the NDF panels to forge a formal peace
agreement, but Jalandoni said that "setting a deadline for the
satisfactory conclusion of the peace talks would not by fruitful."
</P>
<P>
Estrada stressed that the government is ready to resume
fighting with the NDF if the peace talks fail because of NDF's
insistence on a status of belligerency. In fact, the president
ordered the resumption of offensives against NPA on April 19, two
days after the release of Brig. Gen. Obillo.
</P>
<P>
"We will show them that there is only one Constitution, one
government. We will not recognize any other government in the
Philippines," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said the rebels should end their decades-old
insurgency and join his administration instead in helping uplift
the lives of the masses, which is "what they have been fighting
for."
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps, there is no more reason for them to fight the
government because all our projects are aimed at uplifting the
lives of the poor," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the New People's Army and the government soldiers
clashed many times across the country in these days, thus casting
a shadow over the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
