<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ration Card System Successful: Iraqi Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The ration card system adopted by
Iraq following the imposition of U.N. sanctions in distributing
foodstuff to all citizens has proved successful in organizing
family consumption, a Trade Ministry report said.
</P>
<P>
The report, carried by the Iraqi News Agency on Sunday, said
the ministry began applying such a system to "distribute basic
foodstuff on equal basis to all people in Iraq" on September 1,
1990.
</P>
<P>
However, the foodstuff items listed in the ration card can only
meet the minimum need for people to survive - about half the
virtual need of a human being, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The ration card provides only 2,030 calories and 47 grams of
protein daily, while an individual needs at least 2,206 calories
and 64.2 grams of protein each day.
</P>
<P>
Before the imposition of the United Nations sanctions on August
1990, the report said, the ministry allocated some 2.96 billion
U.S. dollars to import foodstuff every year.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions caused great hardships to the Iraqi people. In
late 1996 an oil-for-food deal was reached between Iraq and the
U.N., which allowed Baghdad to export 2 billion dollars worth of
oil every six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling has been raised to 5.2 billion dollars since the
fourth phase which came into effect in May, 1998. But due to the
sagging oil prices and severe shortage of oil spare parts, Iraq
only exported 3 billion dollars worth of oil in the fourth phase.
</P>
<P>
The report blamed the the U.N. Security Council for failing to
fulfill its obligations to secure smooth arrival of foodstuff
purchased by Iraq, 850 days after the oil-for-food plan was
implemented.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq holds the United States and Britain responsible for
impeding the arrival of foodstuff and other materials to Iraq by
premeditatedly suspending the contracts," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
