<HEADLINE> NATO Moves 23 Tanks to Northern Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) has moved 23 Leopard tanks to the border areas
in northern Macedonia over the past few days, said a report by the
Macedonian news agency MIA, which was monitored here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Seven Leopard tanks, along with 190 other military vehicles,
passed Bogorodica on the border between Macedonia and Greece, in
two convoys, between 05:00 a.m. and 07:00 a.m. local time (0300
GMT and 0500 GMT) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two convoys were part of NATO reinforcements to the 125,000
peacekeeping forces in Macedonia, said the MIA report.
</P>
<P>
NATO was reportedly sending a reinforcement of 2,000 German
troops and 2,000 British troops to Macedonia from Greece.
</P>
<P>
The German convoy was on its way to Krivolak while the other
convoy comprising Dutch soldiers was heading for Petrovec. Both
places are just dozens of kilometers away from the border between
Macedonia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The MIA said that another convoy of Leopard tanks passed the
border check point at Bogorodica later Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The convoy was heading for Strumica, also a Macedonian city
near the Macedonia-Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
"With the previous four convoys, 312 German and 142 Dutch
soldiers from the NATO forces entered Macedonia this morning," the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
A large number of howitzers and other military equipment also
crossed the Macedonia-Greece border with the tank convoys.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia has been opposed to NATO's plan to launch a possible
ground offensive from its soil.
</P>
<P>
Macedonian leaders have repeatedly said that no NATO ground
attacks on Yugoslavia will be allowed from the territory of
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
In an exchange of letters with NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana on Friday, Macedonian Foreign Minister Aleksandar Dimitrov
reaffirmed that the NATO troops in Macedonia are not offensive.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO, embarrassed with its failure to make
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic bow after a month of massive
air bombardments on Yugoslavia, was reportedly planning for a
ground operation in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
