<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebel Group Frees Last Captive Soldier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The National Democratic Front
(NDF) Sunday released its last hostage, S/Sgt. Wivino Demol, who
had been held captive for 14 months and 15 days, paving the way
for the resumption of peace talks between the NDF and the
government.
</P>
<P>
Demol was released around 12:30 (04:30 GMT) in Longos, Laguna,
the northern Philippines, according to the official Philippine
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Demol was reunited with his wife and children 30 minutes after
he was freed, and Lydia Demol cried when she saw her husband for
the first time in over 14 months, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference following his release, Demol said one
good thing that happened during his captivity was that he was able
to quit smoking and drinking.
</P>
<P>
Demol, who was captured in the town of Rodriguez, Rizal
Province, on February 9, 1998, was the fifth and last captive
freed by the NDF this month.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the NDF freed three army officers and one police
officer they captured in Mindanao and Bicol, the southern
Philippines, in February and March.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group abducted the five in an attempt to exchange
"prisoners of war" with the government. But President Joseph
Estrada rejected the demand and suspended peace talks indefinitely
with the NDF in February.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the government said it would resume peace talks with
the NDF if the rebel group freed all the five hostages safely.
</P>
<P>
Like the other four hostages, Demol will undergo intensive
debriefing by the Intelligence Service of the Armed Forces of the
Philippines (ISAFP) in Camp Aguinaldo, Manila, the Philippine News
Agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
