<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Sets Up Task Force Against Sub-Standard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has set up
a task force to tackle the problem of sub-standard products since
imitations flood local markets, a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Deputy Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry,
Jazzman Chikwakwa said lately that "as a concerned government, we
can not allow such a state of affairs."
</P>
<P>
The task force was made up of officers from the Zambia Bureau
of Standards, the Zambia Revenue Authority, police, officials from
the ministries of health, local government and housing as well as
the commerce ministry, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the deputy minister toured some markets in capital
Lusaka in his campaign against expired foodstuffs, finding various
expired items on the shelves in dozens of supermarkets and other
retail outlets, the Sunday Times of Zambia reported.
</P>
<P>
In some cases, some supermarket owners simply defaced the
places where the production and expire dates are supposed to be
displayed on the products, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The problem is further exacerbated by the equally growing spate
of imitation products now flooding the market, it said.
</P>
<P>
A whole range of shadow "industries" engaged in this are now in
 operation, churning out various consumer products.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Bureau of Standards, the government watchdog for
product standards and quality, feels the scourge is likely to grow
in view of the stiff competition entailed by economic
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
A senior standard official, Mataa Mukelabai was quoted as
saying that unable to beat the competition, an increasing number
of entrepreneurs have resorted to producing and selling imitation
products of popular brand names.
</P>
<P>
"Economic liberalization does not mean flouting regulations and
selling sub-standard products. Liberalization means competition
and quality products," the deputy minister stressed, adding that
those who can't produce quality products should not try to hide
behind other manufacturers' brand names.
</P>
<P>
"We'll ensure stern action is taken against all the culprits,"
Chikwakwa said.
</P>
<P>
Practically all manner of consumer products, from fruit juices
to washing detergents, electrical appliances to motor vehicle
spare parts, designer label clothes to designer label cosmetics
and several other items, all occupy space on many a selling shelf.
</P>
<P>
Mukelabai said as long as consumers are willing to buy products
of suspect quality simply because they have lower prices, it would
be difficult to combat the imitation scourge.
</P>
<P>
However, concerned at the growing trend and the serious
implications this has on the health and safety of consumers, the
Zambian government is stepping up its campaign against such
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
