<HEADLINE> Jordan Asks Israel to Reopen Palestinian Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has asked Israel to rescind
its decision to close the Orient House in East Jerusalem, known as
the unofficial headquarters of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, the Jordan Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the Israeli government dated on Saturday,
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah Khatib voiced his country`s
concern over the Israeli action to close the Orient House, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli move was unjustifiable and would further complicate
the situation in East Jerusalem while encroaching on the
Palestinian rights to self-determination, Khatib said in the
message.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Israeli government to reconsider its decision
to avoid any adverse effects on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Thursday ordered the
closure of the Orient House following a meeting of Palestinian
officials and some Arab diplomats in the house on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu claimed that the meeting violated agreements barring
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) activity in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have denounced the move as a campaign ploy by
Netanyahu, noting that any attempt to close the Orient House,
registered as a private residence, would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is currently lagging in opinion polls behind his
main rival for premiership Labor Party chief Ehud Barak for the
upcoming Israeli elections slated for May 17.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians railed against Netanyahu for trying to
fabricate an allegation of Palestinian threat to Israeli
sovereignty over Jerusalem as a central theme for his reelection
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied East Jerusalem in 1967 and later illegally
annexed it as part of its capital, while the Palestinians hope to
make the sector the capital of their own state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
