<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, April 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- Over 150,000 Italians Saturday staged a demonstration
in Rome protesting against NATO bombing against Yugoslavia and
calling for restoration of peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The widow of assassinated Israeli former Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, the Nobel peace prize winner and former Israeli Premier
Shimon Peres took part in the demonstration, organized by Italy's
largest ruling party of the Left Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat had also been
expected to show up but in the end sent a representative to back
the demonstration. (Italy-Demonstration-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- Two NATO planes violated Bulgarian airspace Friday
night, the Government Information Service told the Bulgarian
Telegraph Agency.
</P>
<P>
It was probably the result of a temporary deviation from the
set course by the pilots of the two planes, according to a press
release.
</P>
<P>
The planes were 30 kilometers deep into Bulgarian airspace and
were monitored by the Bulgarian Air Defense from 1:30 a.m. to 01:
35 a.m. local time. (Bulgaria-NATO Plane)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- The government and the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) resumed talks Saturday to discuss
an agenda for a possible peace process.
</P>
<P>
Government representatives and delegates of FARC, the largest
rebel group in the country, met at the demilitarized zone in San
Vicente del Caguan, where they had met last Tuesday and Wednesday
after a three-month interruption. (Colombia-Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- NATO brushed off a proposal on Saturday by
Ukraine's President Leonid Kuchma on peaceful settlement of the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome very much the tireless diplomatic efforts of the
Ukrainian government and of President Kuchma himself to resolve
the crisis," NATO Secretary General Javier Solana told a joint
news conference with Kuchma after he met NATO's 19 leaders. (NATO-
Ukraine-Proposal
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Nineteen NATO member nations on Saturday approved
a new strategic concept that breaks the original "collective
defense" doctrine and assumes broader functions to take actions
outside alliance territory.
</P>
<P>
After overcoming Turkish objections, leaders also approved a
statement recognizing the 15-nation European Union's growing role
in security and defense and its right to approve military action
where the alliance as a whole is not engaged.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton gave this new EU function a guarded
welcome, saying: "I think it will strengthen the capability of the
alliance, and I think it will actually help to maintain America's
involvement with NATO." (NATO-New Strategy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Three civilians were killed and 14 wounded in the
east of Sri Lanka by shelling and gunfire following an attack by
the Tamil rebels on a police sentry in the early hours of Sunday
morning, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted police as saying the rebel assault, around
12:40 a.m., was repulsed with no damage to its sentry by the
lagoon in Eravur, 16 kilometers north of Batticaloa.
</P>
<P>
The police said the rebels had traded mortar and gunfire
following the attack. Civilians in the neighborhood were wounded
and killed in the crossfire. (Sri Lanka-Rebel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The anti-government National Democratic Front (NDF)
freed a government soldier Sunday in the northern Philippines,
paving the way for the resumption of peace talks between the
government and the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
S/Sgt. Wivino Demol, who was abducted by the NDF's armed wing --
New People's Army (NPA) -- a year ago, was freed in Sta. Cruz,
Laguna, 30 kilometers south of Manila, around 12:30 (04:30) Sunday,
according to an SNN television report.
</P>
<P>
Demol was captured in Rizal, the northern Philippines, last
year while disguising as a rice trader. (Phillipines-Hostage
Release) 
</P>
</TEXT>
