<HEADLINE> URGENT: Philippine Rebel Group Frees Last Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The anti-government National
Democratic Front (NDF) freed a government soldier Sunday in the
northern Philippines, paving the way for the resumption of peace
talks between the government and the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
S/Sgt. Wivino Demol, who was abducted by the NDF's armed wing
-- New People's Army (NPA) -- a year ago, was freed in Sta. Cruz,
Laguna, 30 kilometers south of Manila, around 12:30 (04:30)
Sunday, according to an SNN television report.
</P>
<P>
Demol was captured in Rizal, the northern Philippines, last
year while disguising as a rice trader.
</P>
<P>
The NDF had held captive five government troops but four of
them had been released in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Those who were released earlier this month were Brig. Gen.
Victor C. Obillo, Capt. Eduardo Montealto, Sgt. Alipio Lozano and
Police Chief Insp. Roberto Bernal.
</P>
<P>
The NDF abducted these army officers in an attempt to exchange
"prisoners of war" with the government. However, President Joseph
Estrada rejected the rebels' demand and indefinitely suspended
peace talks with the group two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Later, the government said it would resume peace talks with the
NDF soon if the rebel group freed all the five hostages safely.
</P>
</TEXT>
