<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Animal Poachers Crushed in Hoh Xil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A suspected poacher of wild
animals has been killed and two of his accomplices wounded by
Chinese police in the Hoh Xil Nature Reserve.
</P>
<P>
And forty other suspected poachers have been arrested by the
police who believe the gang has been capturing rare wild animals.
</P>
<P>
The raid was carried out by the State Forestry Administration (
SFA) and supported by officials from Qinghai Province and the
Xinjiang Uygur and Tibet autonomous regions who are keen to crack
down on the growing problem of the poaching and smuggling of
Tibetan antelopes.
</P>
<P>
Since earlier this month rangers have confiscated more than 500
Tibetan antelope furs, 288 antelope heads, four Yak furs, three
Yak heads, nine rifles, more than 7,900 rounds of ammunition and a
dozen vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, which is located at the junction of Qinghai,
Xinjiang and Tibet, is home to more than 20 rare animal species
like the Yak and Tibetan antelope which are under state protection.
</P>
<P>
The SFA and the Ministry of Public Security have sent a letter
of appreciation to the rangers who are taking action in Hoh Xil.
After their activities were covered by China Central Television
and other major news media the Chinese people have expressed their
great concern about the poaching.
</P>
<P>
Rangers will continue to track down and arrest suspects in the
middle part of the natural reserve, sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
