<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wizards Strickland Arrested for DWI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Washington Wizards guard Rod
Strickland is in trouble again.
</P>
<P>
Strickland was arrested early this morning in the District of
Columbia and charged with driving while intoxicated and reckless
driving. He was released on citation and is scheduled to appear in
court on May 7.
</P>
<P>
According to police spokesman Joseph Gentile, two sergeants in
an unmarked police car spotted a gold Mercedes Benz change lanes
without signaling and then pass three red lights at approximately
3:35 a.m.
</P>
<P>
When Strickland was pulled over, he failed a field sobriety
test and refused to take a blood-alcohol test.
</P>
<P>
The alleged incident occurred hours after the Wizards suffered
an 89-78 home loss to the Atlanta Hawks. Strickland had 10 points
and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
In April 1998, Strickland was convicted of driving while
impaired. He was ordered to perform community service and placed
on one-year probation, which expired earlier in the month.
</P>
<P>
Wizards general manager Wes Unseld issued the following
statement regarding Strickland's arrest.
</P>
<P>
"The Wizards organization is disappointed this event has
occurred because Rod has been exceptional this year in terms of
the fans and his commitment to the franchise. We hope to garner
more information, but for now the situation is in the hands of the
legal authorities."
</P>
<P>
Strickland, 32, signed a four-year, 40 million U.S. dollars
contract with the Wizards before the start of the lockout-
shortened season. He is averaging 15.5 points and 10.1 assists in
37 games.
</P>
<P>
Although regarded as one of the league's top point guards,
Strickland has often tested management's patience. He often is
late for practices and was involved in a fight with teammate Tracy
Murray last year.
</P>
<P>
Strickland was an All-NBA Second Team selection following the
1997-98 campaign, when he averaged 17.8 points and led the league
with 10.5 assists per game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
