<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Leaders Approve New Strategic Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen NATO member nations
on Saturday approved a new strategic concept that breaks the
original "collective defense" doctrine and assumes broader
functions to take actions outside alliance territory.
</P>
<P>
After overcoming Turkish objections, leaders also approved a
statement recognizing the 15-nation European Union's growing role
in security and defense and its right to approve military action
where the alliance as a whole is not engaged.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton gave this new EU function a guarded
welcome, saying: "I think it will strengthen the capability of the
alliance, and I think it will actually help to maintain America's
involvement with NATO."
</P>
<P>
The Washington Summit Communique, issued after the meeting by
the leaders, said that the new concept reaffirms commitment to
collective defense and the trans-Atlantic link.
</P>
<P>
The updated concept also "presents an Alliance ready and with a
full range of capabilities to enhance the security and stability
of the Euro-Atlantic area."
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the alliance will "provide one of the
indispensable foundations for a stable Euro-Atlantic security
environment...in which no country would be able to intimidate or
coerce any other through the threat or use of force."
</P>
<P>
NATO will also "deter and defend against any threat of
aggression against any NATO member states" and "stand ready, case-
by-case and by consensus...to contribute to effective conflict
prevention and to engage actively in crisis management, including
crisis response management."
</P>
<P>
Meeting under the shadow of NATO's airstrikes against
Yugoslavia over Kosovo, the leaders spent most of the second day
of their 50th anniversary summit discussing future missions beyond
NATO borders.
</P>
<P>
There were differences on the interpretation of the new
strategic concept.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac hailed it as a triumph for
France and said it meant "NATO cannot and will not be able to act
without the authorization of this international recognition,"
referring to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
To allow NATO exceptions from U.N. jurisdiction would set a
dangerous precedent for states or organizations and could
ultimately lead to "the law of the strongest," he said.
</P>
<P>
But NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, asked whether the
alliance would need a Security Council resolution each time it
intervened outside its territory, said bluntly "No."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said he was pleased that the new
strategic concept endorsed specifically the NATO military campaign
against Yugoslavia over the Kosovo crisis, which did not have an
explicit U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
However, several European allies argued Kosovo was an exception
out of humanitarian purpose, and in other cases, a U.N. mandate
would be imperative.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said U.N. mandates were the
rule but there could be limited exceptions, although NATO could
not simply give itself a mandate to act "out of area." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilians Killed, 14 Wounded in Crossfire in S. Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Three civilians were killed and
14 wounded in the east of Sri Lanka by shelling and gunfire
following an attack by the Tamil rebels on a police sentry in the
early hours of Sunday morning, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted police as saying the rebel assault, around
12:40 a.m., was repulsed with no damage to its sentry by the
lagoon in Eravur, 16 kilometers north of Batticaloa.
</P>
<P>
The police said the rebels had traded mortar and gunfire
following the attack. Civilians in the neighborhood were wounded
and killed in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
Of those killed, two were Tamils and the other a Muslim, said
the reports, quoting Eravur hospital sources.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that of the wounded are 10 Tamils and four
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Police officers said the rebels had come across the lagoon from
Pankudaaveli in the Batticaloa district which is not under the
control of the Sri Lankan security forces.
</P>
<P>
Tamil rebels have been fighting a 16-year separatist war
against the Sri Lankan government for a Tamil homeland in the
north and east of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
