<HEADLINE> NATO Rejects Ukraine's Peace Proposal on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- NATO brushed off a proposal on
Saturday by Ukraine's President Leonid Kuchma on peaceful
settlement of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I welcome very much the tireless diplomatic efforts of the
Ukrainian government and of President Kuchma himself to resolve
the crisis," NATO Secretary General Javier Solana told a joint
news conference with Kuchma after he met NATO's 19 leaders.
</P>
<P>
But Solana indicated the proposal was short of the alliance's
five-point set of demands for the suspension of NATO's airstrikes.
He stressed Belgrade must assent to NATO's presence in Kosovo to
enforce a Western-imposed peace deal.
</P>
<P>
A declaration was issued after Kuchma met with NATO's 19
leaders. The declaration papered over the Kosovo issue by saying
both sides supported a peaceful multi-ethnic and democratic Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The declaration did not mention Kuchma's peace proposal, which
envisages a simultaneous halt to NATO bombardment and deployment
of peacekeepers from neutral nations.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma also proposed a simultaneous ceasefire by Yugoslav
forces in Kosovo, and by ethnic Albanian guerrillas and by NATO
units bombing Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis can be settled only by the concerted efforts of all
the parties involved," Kuchma told the joint news conference.
Ukraine's efforts were not a "solo performance" but a part of
wider international efforts to solve the conflict, he explained.
</P>
<P>
"These (Kosovo) events are taking place not far from our home.
We know what war is like and that is why we are so active in
seeking a peaceful settlement," he said. 
</P>
