<HEADLINE> China Sees Growing Industrial Output Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial sector
continued to grow in the first two months this year, according to
figures released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The added value of industry from January to February increased
by 10.6 percent on an annual basis to 280 billion yuan (33.8
billion U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
The added value of light industry during the period stood at
115.2 billion yuan and that of heavy industry 164.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed an added value of 160.7 billion yuan from the
state owned and state holding enterprises, which accounted for
more than half of the gross industrial output in the two months.
</P>
<P>
Collectively-owned enterprises, a component of the public
assets, reported an added value of 45.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The added value of enterprises with foreign investment and
investment made by Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan amounted to 55.4
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
However, China underwent a decline in industrial growth in
February with a growth rate of only 2.1 percent, as against 17.9
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The statistics covered all enterprises in the state and non-
state sectors with the annual product sales revenue at and above
five million yuan.  
</P>
