<HEADLINE> Pension of Rural Workers to be Worked Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Labor and Social
Security is to unveil a prototype pension system at the turn of
the year for township enterprise workers who are not covered by
the present social security system.
</P>
<P>
The method will be based on experience from eight trial
projects to be started from May this year, "China Daily" quoted
Zhang Shouqi, vice-director of the ministry's rural social
insurance department, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises account for one-third of China's national
economy, and are sure to develop further with the transfer of more
rural labor and the establishment of more small towns, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The number of rural township workers surpassed that of urban
workers to reach 130 million in 1998. However, this large group is
not covered by the temporary social insurance system, which
concentrates on workers with urban residence registration.
</P>
<P>
"How to provide financial support for these farmer employees
after they retire is an unavoidable question, and is crucial to
completing China's social security system," he said.
</P>
<P>
A tentative plan will be drafted in November after summarizing
the experience of the eight projects. It will be discussed in
December.
</P>
<P>
The future rural worker pension system will not take the form
of the existing urban system, which relies on both personally
accumulated funds and a mutual account made up of funds from
individuals, enterprises, and the state.
</P>
<P>
It will rely only on a fund to which individuals contribute
from their salaries. The state will regulate the system to ensure
its smooth operation. The sum of deposit, which is collected
before tax, will not be fixed, but be in proportion with the
worker's salary.
</P>
<P>
The system should complement the urban system to establish a
unified, open, and orderly labor market in the future, Zhang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
