<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (51) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 51 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Which organization shall be responsible for assessing
professional qualifications and issuing certificates for
practicing various professions in the Macao Special Administrative
Region?
</P>
<P>
Like in all countries and regions in the world, only those who
in Macao are professionally qualified and have acquired the
corresponding qualifications can practice in such professions as
law and medicine or as doctors, accountants and architects.
</P>
<P>
Owing to historical reasons, Macao does not have many
professionals among its local residents. Most of its
professionals are either Macao residents who have studied abroad
or people who have come from the mainland, Hong Kong or from
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
There are a few professional organizations in Macao such as
the Association of Auditors, the Association of Accountants, the
Association of Architects, the Society of Traditional Chinese
Medicine, Chinese Society of Medicine and the Association of
Engineers.
</P>
<P>
However, they are small in number, and there is no widely
representative and authoritative professional organization in
Macao. Because of this, it has been the responsibility of the
Macao Government to assess and award professional qualifications.
</P>
<P>
In view of this, Article 129 of the Basic Law stipulates that
the Government of the Macao Special Administrative Region shall,
on its own, establish a system concerning the professions and,
based on impartiality and rationality, formulate provisions for
assessing professional qualifications or qualifications for
practice in the various professions and issuing corresponding
certificates.
</P>
<P>
It is clear from this provision that the formulation of the
provisions for assessing professional qualifications and the
issuance of certificates for practice shall be conducted by the
Government on a fair and reasonable basis, and no professional
organizations shall be empowered to do so.
</P>
<P>
Will those who have already acquired professional
qualifications or qualifications for professional practice need to
re-register with the authorities for reassessing their
qualifications after the return of Macao?
</P>
<P>
Article 129 of the Basic Law clearly stipulates that persons
with professional qualifications or qualifications for
professional practice obtained prior to the establishment of the
Macao Special Administrative Region may retain their previous
qualifications in accordance with the relevant regulations of the
Macao Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
In other words, those who have previously obtained their
professional qualifications or qualifications for professional
practice need not re-register their qualifications through re-
examination and re-assessment.
</P>
<P>
The Government of the Macao Special Administrative Region
shall recognize their previous qualifications, so long as they are
consistent with the relevant laws and provisions concerning the
system on professionals of the Macao Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
For instance, accountants may continue to operate in the
accounting profession. It is also provided in this Article that
the Government of the Macao Special Administrative Region shall,
in accordance with the relevant regulations, recognize the
professions and the professional organizations that are recognized
prior to the establishment of the Region.
</P>
<P>
The Government of the Macao Special Administrative Region may,
as required by social development and in consultation with the
parties concerned, recognize new professions and professional
organizations.
</P>
<P>
These provisions of the Basic Law will not only ensure the
continuity of the existing system concerning professions in Macao,
but also help gradually develop and improve such a system of the
Macao Special Administrative Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (52) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 52 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
What will happen to offices set up by Taiwan in Macao after
the return of Macao?
</P>
<P>
Both Taiwan and Macao are inalienable parts of the territory
of the People's Republic of China. At present, Taiwan and Macao
maintain contacts and exchanges in the economic, trade, tourism
and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Especially with the opening of direct air links between Taiwan
and Macao after the completion of the international airport in
Macao, they will enjoy closer and more frequent exchanges and ties
in these fields. According to the one China principle, Taiwan is
not allowed to set up any official missions or offices in Macao.
But it may set up economic and trade offices there.
</P>
<P>
After China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Macao,
Taiwan's economic and trade offices in Macao and their staff can
in principle stay on and the two regions can continue to maintain
and develop contacts in the economic, trade, tourism and other
fields.
</P>
<P>
However,Taiwan should not set up any official missions in the
Macao Special Administrative Region. Taiwan's offices in Macao
and their staff should strictly abide by the one China principle,
the Basic Law and other laws of the Macao Special Administrative
Region.
</P>
<P>
They should not engage themselves in activities aimed at
creating two Chinas or "one China, one Taiwan", or do anything
harmful to the development of the relations across the Taiwan
Straits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Aims to Increase Exports of Electrical Appliances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China will try to increase its
exports of electrical appliances by 10 percent this year to 3.9
billion US dollars, Business Weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
The growth target is propelled by a weak growth on the domestic
market. Many manufacturers have turned to international
specialized exhibitions, employed qualified sales agencies,
established international sales networks, found distribution
centers and set up factories in foreign countries, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Many enterprises will also increase investment to speed up the
pace of technical renovations and new product development in a bid
to win market shares internationally.
</P>
<P>
Exports of air conditioners and microwave ovens with high
technical contents had the largest growth rate last year, up by 53
and 61 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Appliances producers are targeting new markets including Europe,
the Middle East, South America and Africa, says the report.
</P>
<P>
China's domestic market of appliances have witnessed cutthroat
competitions over the past few years. A new wave of price-cutting
campaign has been launched lately among leading manufacturers of
color TV sets.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the General Administration of Customs show
that China's exports of electrical appliances grew 9.3 percent in
1998 compared with a year ago, hitting 3.51 billion US dollars.
</P>
