<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chia's Fishing Ban Unlikely to Cause Market Fluctuations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The fishing ban in the South
China Sea in June and July will not cause a big fluctuation on the
domestic and international aquatic products markets, China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ban, to be imposed by the Ministry of Agriculture for the
first time in the South China Sea north of 12 degrees north
latitude, is aimed at protecting marine resources and guaranteeing
sustainable development in the fisheries industry, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Yang Jian, director of the Ministry's fisheries
bureau, as saying that the ban would not influence prices on the
domestic market nor reduce exports in the long run.
</P>
<P>
The aquatic products market in China was basically in an
oversupply condition, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
The average price of aquatic products decreased during the
first quarter of this year, according to industry statistics.
</P>
<P>
Also the ban only forbids fishing methods that kill large
amounts of small fry, while other methods can be continued to
catch high-grade large fish, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Fish breeding has developed rapidly in China and this will help
make up for any scarcity caused by the fishing ban, it said,
adding that Chinese fishing vessels may join other countries to
fish their waters and transport the catch to China.
</P>
<P>
Yang admitted, however, that shortage may occur in the supply
of some varieties in some areas.
</P>
<P>
But the smooth circulation channels in the market will
facilitate the transfer of such products to those areas in need,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
In short, the overall aquatic market nationwide is going to
remain stable, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the fishing ban will not pose a threat to China's
aquatic products exports as there remains some stock to supply the
international market, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited past experience as saying that a fishing ban can
ultimately stimulate exports of aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Last year China imposed a fishing ban for one month in the East
China Sea but exports of aquatic products went up 8.9 percent to
one million tons, China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Overfishing in the South China Sea for many years has almost
depleted its fishery resources, resulting in many idle fishing
boats and reductions in fishermen's earnings, it said.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that fisheries industry authorities would take
measures to restrict the output of marine fishing in the near
future to achieve healthy progress in the industry.
</P>
<P>
This year marine fishing output is scheduled to realize zero
growth over last year's 14.96 million tons, which was nearly eight
percent more than the figure for 1997, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
China's total output of aquatic products rose 8.5 percent to 39
million tons last year. Industry officials predicted that the
output for this year will continue to grow, but only at a lower
rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
