<HEADLINE> World Bank Tones Down Italy's Economic Growth in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Italian economy will grow by
only 1.4 percent in 1999, the latest forecasts released by the
World Bank show.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's figures are more pessimistic than those
recently released by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
Italian government.
</P>
<P>
The IMF revised its 1999 growth forecast for Italy down from 2.
5 percent to 1.9 percent in December, and then earlier this month
revised it downward again, arriving at 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Treasury Ministry, meanwhile, has also revised its
figures down, moving from the initial growth forecasts of 1.9
percent-2.5 percent to 1.5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank was more optimistic about the prospects of
Italy's economic growth in 2000, forecasting a jump in gross
domestic product to 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Regarding inflation, the World Bank forecast an inflation rate
of 1.5 percent for Italy in 1999, rising to 1.8 percent in 2000,
compared to IMF's 1.3 percent for 1999 and 1.5 percent for 2000.
</P>
<P>
Economic observers here said that the recession of Italy's
economy has been caused by NATO's attacks against Yugoslavia and
insufficient stimulating policies on national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
