<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Dominates ADB Activity in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said that it devoted much of its energy to easing Asia's
unprecedented crisis throughout 1998 by promoting growth, reducing
poverty and supporting human development in the region.
</P>
<P>
In its Annual Report 1998 released here Monday, the
Manila-based bank said that 1998 was "a difficult and damaging
year for Asia's economies" and economic growth in the region was
sharply curtailed.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout 1998, the bank devoted much of its energy to
responding to Asia's unhappy and unprecedented circumstances," it
said.
</P>
<P>
During the year, the bank said, it continued to emphasize its
five strategic objectives -- promoting economic growth, reducing
poverty, supporting human development, improving the status of
women and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
The bank's total lending in 1998 amounted to about 6 billion
U.S. dollars for 57 projects, compared with 9.4 billion dollars in
the previous year when lending had been boosted by an exceptional
large financial sector program loan of 4 billion dollars to South
Korea, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
"The financial sector again received the largest share of
lending (nearly 1.7 billion dollars). Borrowings amounted to 9.6
billion dollars, the largest ever in one year," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said its cofinancing mobilized from all sources
amounted to about 3 billion dollars for 24 projects, including 950
million dollars for Thailand's export financing facility, close to
50 percent of the bank's total lending.
</P>
<P>
"This level of cofinancing, a 67 percent increase over that in
1997, was significant given the difficult market conditions," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The bank also said cumulative ADB lending, since the bank began
operation in 1966 up to the end of 1998, amounts to 77.3 billion
dollars for 1,500 projects in 37 developing members.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1966, the ADB engages in a wide range of social
and economic development activities aimed at improving the welfare
of the people in the region.
</P>
<P>
The bank's stock is owned by its 57 members, 41 of which are
from the Asian and Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
