<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Urges Members to Adopt Good Governance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Monday urged its members to adopt good governance and
anti-corruption practices to promote economic development in the
Asian and Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
In its Annual Report 1998 released here, the bank said issues
of governance are at the center of many of the most pressing
challenges confronting countries throughout the Asian and Pacific
region today.
</P>
<P>
The bank defined governance as "the manner in which power is
exercised in the management of a country's social and economic
resources for development."
</P>
<P>
The bank said that in East and Southeast Asia, the need for
greater transparency and accountability in regulating the
financial sector has been one of the key problems behind the
currency turmoil, corporate bankruptcies and falling stock markets
that have plagued the region since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
In South Asia, the ADB said, issues of restricting the reach of
state intervention and improving the delivery of basic services,
such as health care and education, are high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Economies in transition in Central and Southeast Asia are
grappling with re-defining the role of state, shifting the balance
between central and local power and providing civil service
employees with appropriate skills for managing a market economy,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said each nation's path to good governance is
different, but governments face similar responsibilities in that
they need to establish a basic policy framework, provide critical
goods and services, protect and administer the rule of law and
advance social equity.
</P>
<P>
In executing these responsibilities, governments need to
perform a variety of similar tasks, such as organizing themselves
to formulate and coordinate specific policies and mobilizing human
and financial resources to implement their policies, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank's approach to helping its developing members improve
governance practices has sought to overcome problems of diversity,
the bank added.
</P>
<P>
In view of the corrosive effect of corruption on developing
countries, the bank also encouraged its members to adopt
anti-corruption measures.
</P>
<P>
Corruption exacts a heavy price from developing economies in
terms of reducing investment, increasing capital costs while
lowering asset life and hindering the development of a robust and
competitive private sector, it said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB annual report also reviewed the bank's operations
totaling 6.2 billion U.S. dollars in loans, equity investments and
technical assistance to its 57 members in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
