<HEADLINE>     Philippines' Pacquiao Retains WBC Flyweight Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippines' Manny Pacquiao
retained his World Boxing Council (WBC) flyweight crown Saturday
night by knocking out Mexican challenger Gabriel Mira in the
fourth round of their scheduled 12-round bout at the Araneta
Coliseum in Manila.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year old Pacquiao, using his right-left combination,
floored his Mexican challenger for three times in the fourth round
that forced American referee Richard Steele to stop the fight.
</P>
<P>
His knockout victory came after two minutes and 45 seconds in
the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
But Pacquiao admitted that he was also hurt by the right hook
punch delivered by his opponent in the second round.
</P>
<P>
The Filipino fighter worked methodically in the opening of the
fourth round until he scored a solid left-right combinations on
Mira's face for the first knockdown. Pacquiao continued his
relentless attack that sent his foe down for the second time.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican challenger showed his fighting heart, exchanging
blows with Pacquiao but the Filipino fighter connected solid
combination and finished the fight with left and right hook
punches.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Pacquiao's record improved to 26-1 (win-loss)
that highlighted with 17 knockout wins while Mira absorbed his
eight loss in 28 fights.
</P>
<P>
The first round saw the Mexican challenger a little bit
aggressive,demonstrating a better footwork, but Pacquiao delivered
a solid left upper punch to send a strong signal.
</P>
<P>
As both fighters exchanging blows at the start of the second
round, Pacquiao saw an opening in the face of the challenger,
delivered a left uppercut that sent Mira in the canvas for the
first time in the bout.
</P>
<P>
In the third round, Pacquiao punished Mira with telling blows
that put the Mexican fighter in trouble for several times.
</P>
<P>
Pacquiao captured the 112-pound crown from Thailand's Chatchai
Sasakul in Bangkok last December. 
</P>
