<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Revamp Water Pricing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A new pricing system is to encourage investors to run water
facilities efficiently, the newspaper's Business Weekly quoted an
official of the Ministry of Water Resources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The price of water for farm use will be at least tripled to
cover production costs, ensure proper water management, and raise
the potential for profits, the newspaper said, adding that some
400 billion cubic meters of water, or 70 percent of total water
supply, are used for farming each year.
</P>
<P>
Government administrations were exclusively responsible for
water distribution in China for decades while market forces were
shut out and private capital banned until a few years ago, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The price of water for urban residents and industrial and
commercial uses will also be raised, it said.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified official said there was room for higher prices
in the cities as water pay accounts for only two percent of the
cost of industrial production and urban household expenditure.
</P>
<P>
A market driven water distribution system is likely to be
established in urban areas next year in line with the country's
water industry policy, the official said.
</P>
<P>
However, the pricing reform may not be completed in rural areas
on schedule as the issue of property rights regarding water
facilities is complicated and surveillance is difficult, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Water prices in China have been kept artificially low for
decades by a rigid planning system, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Per capita water resources in China are only one-fourth of the
world average and the government is being urged to take action on
the country's deterioration water situation before it is too late,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the new pricing system is expected to help
foster a market that will appeal to investors, the ministry
official said, adding that the reform-oriented water industry
policy encourages diverse investment sourcing.
</P>
<P>
A revolution is already taking place as private capital,
including foreign direct investment, has flowed into small water
conservancy and tap water projects.
</P>
<P>
In Zhejiang Province, private water projects have already proved
themselves to be efficient.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, said that the government would remain
the owner and only investor in most medium-sized and all large
water projects for some time.
</P>
<P>
Many major water facilities also have flood-control and drought-
prevention functions, rather than being first-and-foremost profit-
making concerns.
</P>
<P>
The risks would be high for independent companies, and the
government cannot shoulder the risks for them, the ministry
official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
