<HEADLINE> Mali Beats Uruguay to Take WYC Bronze Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Mali, the only African hope at the
10th FIFA World Youth Championship, beat Uruguay to win a third
place, the African team's best ever achievement in WYC history.
</P>
<P>
Mali's superior speed gave them the edge in a fairly uneventful
first half, but goalkeeper Carini should have held Keita Seydou's
free-kick that gave the Africans their half-time lead at the 30th
minute.
</P>
<P>
Both teams were more enterprising after the interval and
created several good chances but failed to take the best ones.
Mali retained their composure on the verge of their greatest
international achievement to date.
</P>
<P>
The Malian boys, termed by some as "outsiders" after their
found their way to the semifinal of the world youth tournament,
remained the only African team at the Nigeria '99, after the
continent's youth champions and runners-up, Ghana's Black
Satellite and hosts Nigeria's Flying Eagles were kicked out of the
match.
</P>
<P>
The Africans had placed high expectations on the tournament,
which is hosted for the first time in history by a Sub-Sahara
country. Ghana and Nigeria have been taken as Africa's hope to win
golden cup for the continent, but both failed.
</P>
<P>
Africa's other teams, host Nigeria, Ghana, Cameroon and Zambia
had been very promising in the first round of matches.
</P>
<P>
Mali's dream of a final ticket on the WYC was broken by Spain
at the semi-final, when the later win 3-1 over the African team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Hailed as Heroes While Spain Wins WYC Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish team held up the golden
cup after beating Japan 4-0 at the 10th FIFA World Youth Cup in
Lagos Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish showed their strength before 3,8000 spectators in
Lagos with an excellent start, taking the lead after just five
minutes on a free-kick by Saludes Barkero.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish midfield curtain proved impenetrable for Japan who
has hardly got into their game. The Spanish forwards cruised time
and again through the shaky Japanese defense with Coira Pablo
adding another two goals to his tally.
</P>
<P>
While Japan's astounding run through the competition ended
fruitless, the Spanish dominated also the second half with
Francisco Gabriel scoring another goal at the 51st minute.
</P>
<P>
A 4-0 victory won Spanish FIFA WYC golden cup.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese, who had been hailed as heroes with series of
victories at the Nigeria FIFA tournament, met their Waterloo,
ending fruitless against the Europeans, to echo their coach,
Frenchman Phillippe Troussier's words of satisfaction with a
second place at the world youth competition.
</P>
<P>
At the eve of the final match, Troussier, known in the football
circle as "white witch doctor" said that Japan "has already won by
just getting to the final and knowing that we at least have the
silver."
</P>
<P>
History really repeats.
</P>
<P>
The match between Japan and Spain at the FIFA World Youth
Championship, marked the second encounter between an Asian and a
European team for the title -- surprisingly with the same score.
</P>
<P>
Back in 1981, West Germany beat the surprise team of Qatar 4-0
for the trophy, now Spain, another European power beat Japan, also
4-0.
</P>
<P>
If the silver medal by the small Asian country of Qatar was a
big surprise, the Japanese boys who came to Nigeria as underdogs,
and for a time termed as "outsiders" when they entered the semi-
finals, have silenced the surprise bustles over the Asians' win
after beating U.S., England, Portugal, Mexico and Uruguay,
especially with Japanese boys' 2-1 win over Uruguay to get their
ticket for the final match against Spain.
</P>
<P>
They won instead showers of praise worldwide.
</P>
<P>
A FIFA press release even carried sentences which run as
follows: The continent is noted for its mastery of the martial
arts, But there has been a full blown development of soccer in the
far east generally and in Japan particularly which resulted in the
Japanese gaining their first qualification for the senior World
Cup at France '98.
</P>
<P>
But at the youth level, Japan cannot really raise its head high
amongst the best in the world......All that really has changed.
</P>
<P>
Taking Japanese team's achievement at the youth tournament as a
surprising promotion for world football, FIFA President Blatter,
on seeing Japan, along with teams from Africa, South America and
Europe, enter the semi-final, even said that it is encouraging to
see a balanced development of the sport.
</P>
<P>
Troussier, the Frenchman who is leading the Japanese boys to
such a glory, had predicted well before Japanese team got its
ticket for the final that "we should be in the finals because we
worked very hard to get to this stage of the competition."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese tried to continue their amazing run at the final,
with the loss of their captain Shinji Ono who is serving a one-
match ban following two yellow cards in the previous matches.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese boys, though failed to win the first place in
Nigeria, with a fruitless 90 minutes fight against the Spanish,
has already been taken as a big success in the whole Japan, where
people have been celebrating their boys victory these days.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts have even begun to think that the Japanese boys
excellent performances at the Nigeria '99 have given Asian
football a big push, like what Michael Chang offered Asians in the
tennis world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as the silver medalists' coach, Troussier's
extensive team preparations back home in Japan, in France and in
Africa have also paid off. Lost his job as Nigeria's Super Eagle
at the France '98 World Cup,
</P>
<P>
Troussier was welcomed as a hero in Nigeria when his Japanese
team won one victory after another.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
