<HEADLINE> Keegan: United Euro Win Boost England </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- England manager Kevin Keegan paid
his own tribute to the Manchester United stars who have helped
English football back onto Europe's center stage.
</P>
<P>
United's breathtaking comeback against Juventus in midweek has
given his England squad an adrenaline shot before this week's much-
maligned friendly international in Hungary. Now Keegan wants Alex
Ferguson's warriors to lift the Champions' Cup in May and send the
country into the summer's vital Euro 2000 double-header on the
crest of a wave.
</P>
<P>
Keegan said Saturday: "Their success gives English football
tremendous credibility. Now they've got to go on and win it and
then people will say English football is right back there at the
top of the tree. We can all gain confidence from them and their
success."
</P>
<P>
United's England stars face another month of high-octane
football after the Premiership has closed and that prompted
Keegan's offer to rest two of Ferguson's stars from the Hungary
fixture.
</P>
<P>
David Beckham and Gary Neville will sit it out and Keegan also
agreed to omit Tony Adams and Ray Parlour from his usual Arsenal
contingent as the Gunners defend their title.
</P>
<P>
United will still be gunning for more glory once the league
season ends. They take on Newcastle in the FA Cup final at Wembley
on Saturday May 22, before jetting out to Barcelona to face Bayern
Munich in the Champions' Cup final the following Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The England players will join Keegan's squad for a week of
preparation before crunch games against Sweden, at Wembley on June
5, and Bulgaria four days later in Sofia.
</P>
<P>
Keegan said: "It will be a great boost for England if United
can beat Bayern.
</P>
<P>
"In my experience as a player, when you're going like that, you
get in the zone and games can't come quickly enough. They didn't
look tired in extra time against Arsenal at Villa Park.
</P>
<P>
"Bill Shankly used to say: 'Don't listen boys' if the press
were told players they must be tired." 
</P>
</TEXT>
