<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doherty's Fightback in Snooker Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Ken Doherty produced a superb
fightback at the World Snooker Championships in Sheffield, England
on Saturday when he won seven out of eight frames and snatch a 13-
11 win over Nigel Bond in the second round.
</P>
<P>
Bond resumed 10-6 ahead but Doherty won the first three frames
after errors from the Derbyshire professional.
</P>
<P>
In frame 17 Bond missed the blue to let Doherty clear up and
two frames later a missed green let Doherty clear again and then
win on a respotted black.
</P>
<P>
Bond won the next to go 11-9 ahead but Doherty hit back,
leading for the first time at 12-11 before sealing victory and
taking his place in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
"At 10-6 down it looked pretty ominous," said Doherty, "but
winning three of today's first four frames gave me a realistic
chance.
</P>
<P>
"Something wasn't there yesterday but I just found it today and
that was more pleasing than anything.
</P>
<P>
"Without my experience of playing here and of lifting that cup
I wouldn't have won that match. That gives you belief and puts you
on a different level."
</P>
<P>
Defending champion John Higgins took just 10 minutes on
Saturday to wrap up a 13-4 victory over Mark King.
</P>
<P>
Higgins was denied a morning off by King after his 8-0 first
session rout as the Romford professional shared Friday's eight
frames with him.
</P>
<P>
But Higgins wasted little time in Saturday's first frame as
breaks of 80 and 28 completed his win.
</P>
<P>
He now faces a quarter-final clash against fellow Scot Alan
McMannus or Stephen Lee.
</P>
<P>
Matthew Stevens reached his second successive Crucible quarter-
final when he beat Tony Drago 13-8.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, Stevens condemned the 10th seeded Drago to a place
outside the top 16 for the first time in five years.
</P>
<P>
The Maltese Falcon started the day 6-2 adrift but two centuries
in three frames put him back in contention.
</P>
<P>
Drago's downfall came in the 20th frame when a miscued red and
a missed green let Stevens in for a 12-8 lead and the Welshman
finished with a century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
