<DOCNO> XIE19990425.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tottenham Former Manager Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League football
club Tottenham Hotspur honored their most successful manager on
Saturday when the road leading up to their White Hart Lane stadium
in north London was named Bill Nicholson Way.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson, 80, became the first manager to win the English
first division and F.A. Cup double in the 20th century and won
England's first European trophy as well as numerous other domestic
cups in a 16-year reign.
</P>
<P>
He joined Spurs from school in 1936. After winning the league
championship with them as a player, he became manager in 1958.
</P>
<P>
His first game was a 10-4 victory over Everton, and he took
Spurs to the double in 1961, and the F.A. Cup and European Cup
Winners' Cup in the following two years.
</P>
<P>
His total haul included one League title, three F.A. Cups,two
League Cups, the European Cup Winners' Cup and the UEFA Cup in
1972.
</P>
<P>
He retired from management in 1974, but returned to work for
the club as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
He is now the club's president and was made a freeman of the
north London Borough of Haringey last year.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's ceremony before Tottenham's premier league game with
West Ham was attended by a host of his former players including
Pat Jennings, Dave Mackay and Martin Peters.
</P>
<P>
"This is a great honor for me. It's nice to see some familiar
faces, some of the smashing players I worked with, "Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson still attends every Spurs home game and was at
Wembley for their League Cup victory over Leicester last month.
</P>
<P>
"It's good to see them winning trophies again, and I am sure
there is more to come under (manager) George Graham," he said. "I
feel the club is making great progress."
</P>
<P>
Former goalkeeper Jennings added: "Bill was one of the all-time
great managers, up there with the likes of (Liverpool's Bill
Shankly and Matt Busby (of Manchester United). He is the last of
that breed.
</P>
<P>
"Bill's record is fantastic and speaks for itself. He brought
the club great success over a long period of time," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
