<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Leaders Approve New Strategic Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen NATO member nations on
Saturday approved a new strategic concept that finally breaks
original "collective defense" doctrine and assumes broader
functions to take actions outside alliance territory.
</P>
<P>
After overcoming Turkish objections, leaders also approved a
statement recognizing the 15-nation European Union's growing
role in security and defense policy and its right to approve
military action where the alliance as a whole is not engaged.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton gave this new EU function a
guarded welcome, saying: "I think it will strengthen the
capability of the alliance, and I think it will actually help to
maintain America's involvement with NATO."
</P>
<P>
Meeting under the shadow of their war with Yugoslavia over
Kosovo, the leaders spent most of the second day of their 50th
anniversary summit discussing future missions beyond NATO
borders.
</P>
<P>
There were differences on the interpretation of the new
strategic concept.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac hailed it as a triumph for
France and said it meant "NATO cannot and will not be able to act
without the authorization of this international recognization,"
referring to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
To allow NATO exceptions from U.N. jurisdiction would set a
dangerous precedent for states or organizations and could
ultimately lead to "the law of the strongest," he said.
</P>
<P>
But NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, asked whether the
alliance would need a Security Council resolution each time it
intervened outside its territory, said bluntly "no".
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said he was pleased the new
strategic concept endorsed specifically the NATO military campaign
against Yugoslavia over the Kosovo crisis, which did not have an
explicit U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
However, Several European allies argued Kosovo was an
exception out of humanitarian purpose, and in other cases, a
U.N. mandate would be imperative.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said U.N. mandates were
the rule but there could be limited exceptions, although NATO
could not simply give itself a mandate to act "out of area."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
