<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Protest NATO's Bombing in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- "Stop the bombing now!" "Stop
big lies!"
</P>
<P>
Thousands of demonstrators gathered outside the White House on
Saturday to condemn NATO's bombing against Yugoslavia as well as
the U.S. media's biased reports on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Most of the protesters are Serbian-Americans from all across
the United States and some from Canada. As of nine o'clock in the
morning, crowds of demonstrators began to stream into the Lafayett
Park behind the White House.
</P>
<P>
Just a few blocks away, leaders from the 19 NATO members are
meeting in the Ronald Reagon International Trade Center to map out
the new strategy and plan to intensify its air campaign against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Here in the park, many of the protesters carried the red, white
and blue flag of Serbia, and nearly everybody raised a sign or a
poster against the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and
war.
</P>
<P>
One sign paraphrases NATO as "NATO = North Atlantic Terrorist
Organization," another read: "NATO = North American Terrorist
Organization" while a third one read:"NATO = Nazi America
Terrorist Organization."
</P>
<P>
As the police lined up along the Pensylvania avenue, the crowds
shouted at the White House: "Hey, hey, U.S.A., how many kids you
killed today?"
</P>
<P>
Several people held a coffin with signs reading:"NATO VAMPIRE,
1949-1999," and marched around the park. The march draws applause
among the crowds.
</P>
<P>
On poster with the picture of the Yugoslav Radio and Television
building bombed by NATO earlier this week is held by a tall
American senior. On the top of the picture, a line of words
read:"What happened to Freedom of Speech"
</P>
<P>
The demonstrator, who refused to be identified, told Xinhua
that he downloaded the picture from the internet. "Nothing in the
building is military, nor is there any government organs inside.
Why should they bomb it?" he said.
</P>
<P>
The crowds chanted slogans like "CNN (the Cable News Network),
Stop Lies, Tell the Truth."
</P>
<P>
Dusan Jelaca, who drove several hours from Boston to join the
rally, told Xinhua that the Western media is always lying about
the crisis. "The refugees were created by NATO's bombing, not by
Serbs as the (U.S.) media alleged," he said, adding, "Whey didn't
they show the casualties of the Serbians on their TV?"
</P>
<P>
He said that he had done a research in the past year and find
that it is the United States that created the crisis because it
had attempted to break up Yugoslavia for the past decade.
"Yugoslavia has to defend its sovereignty," he said.
</P>
<P>
By the noon time, a pray service began. Dozens of black
balloons were released into the sky amid wild cheers. "The
balloons represent those victims killed in the conflict," Natalija
Djunckovic, one of the organizers from the Serbian Unity Congress
in the U.S., told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Djunckovic, who has many relatives in Yugoslavia, was born in
the United States. "My uncles, my cousins are in Serbia hiding in
bombshelters and I lost contact with them four days ago," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"As an American citizen, I feel how we are adrift from our
constitution. We are invading a sovereign nation, we are killing
innocent people," she added.
</P>
<P>
Raising a sign reading "Kosov, Another Vietnam" with one hand
and an American flag with another, Alex Johnson told Xinhua that
he feared that the bombing of Yugoslavia could ignite another
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
"Many Americans are against this illegal and reckless war. If
they does not stop it now, it would lead to another Vietnam," said
the young man, who got up very early in the morning and drove
nearly 10 hours from Detroit to take part in the rally.
</P>
<P>
Stephanie Niketic of Chicago agreed. "NATO is violating every
international law, and is pure imperialism," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Why do we have violence in our schools? why? because we have a
violent government," Niketic said, referring to the school
shooting earlier this week in Denver, Colorado, in which 15 were
killed.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Clinton administration requested Congress to
approve an emergency budget of six billion U.S. dollars for the
airstrike against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Niketic stressed that the U.S. administration should invest
billions of U.S. dollars which it uses to bomb Yugoslavia in
education.
</P>
<P>
"We need to educate our kids to love peace," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
