<HEADLINE> African Leaders, U.S. Firms Begin Trade Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOUSTON, United States, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A five-day
conference between African leaders and U.S. deal makers kicked off
here on Saturday afternoon to explore opportunities for two-way
trade and investment between Africa and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The theme for the 1999 Summit, "transforming natural wealth into
human capital," speaks to one of the most important challenges
facing Africa today.
</P>
<P>
The participants are expected to attend organized recreation
activities on Sunday. A series of workshops will formally start on
Monday, and will draw five heads of state, four prime ministers and
high-level representatives of more than 26 African countries,
senior U.S. government officials and entrepreneurs as well as the
chief executive officials of some of America's largest corporations.
</P>
<P>
The summit follows on the heals of the U.S.-Africa Ministerial
Meeting held in Washington D.C. last month, which involved 100
ministers from 46 African countries.
</P>
<P>
The gathering, entitled "Attracting Capital to Africa Summit," is
aimed at helping create joint ventures between U.S. and African
companies, encouraging U.S. investment in Africa and highlighting
investment opportunities on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Top U.S. government officials expected at the conference include
the secretaries of commerce, energy, transportation.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the summit is not isolated, but rather
an integral part of the redefinition of the U.S. ties with Africa.
</P>
<P>
On April 21, 1997, some 700 people gathered at Chantilly,
Virginia, to participate in a summit to attract American business to
Africa and to celebrate the economic renaissance of African
continent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
