<HEADLINE> Germany Tunes Down Economic Growth Expectation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The German government was more
cautious about the country's economic perspective by tuning down
its expected growth rate for year 1999 to mere 1.5 percent, a
Finance Ministry spokesman said Saturday in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
However, next year the German economy would show 2.5 percent
growth, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Last Autumn, the government's panel of independent economic
advisers predicted a 2.0 percent growth rate in 1999. Until in
March experts had counted on a growth rate of 2.2 percent despite
many crises over the world.
</P>
<P>
But two influential news weeklies, Der Spiegel and Focus, have
expected the German economy to expanse by only 1.6 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
Hans-Olaf Henkel, President of the Federation of German
Industry, said that any expectation for a growth rate higher than
2 percent was impossible to realize.  
</P>
