<HEADLINE> Clinton Pleads for "Patience" with Bombing on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
acknowledging NATO's failure for a quick surrendering of
Yugoslavia by airstrikes, urged patience on Saturday in forcing
Belgrade to accept NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
"In order for this strategy to succeed, we need two things:
vigorous execution and patience," Clinton told a news conference
on the second day of the three-day gathering of the NATO 50th
anniversary summit.
</P>
<P>
He noted that allies bombed Iraq for 44 days before beginning
a ground assault to force Iraqi troops from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Noting the size of the Yugoslav force still in Kosovo,
Clinton said it would take time "to reverse that, but we are
working on it and we will prevail if we execute well with real
determination and if we have the patience."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also declared that the alliance would strongly enforce
an oil embargo against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also sought to ease mounting tensions with Russia --
one supplier of oil to Yugoslavia -- over the Kosovo crisis,
saying he welcomed Russia's efforts for a peace deal over the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Our alliance recognizes the tremendous importance of Russia
to our alliance's future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's foreign minister said on Saturday that his country
would ignore any oil embargo of Yugoslavia, claiming such a move
would violate international law.
</P>
<P>
"We Have to take every reasonable means" to enforce the ban
on oil shipments to Belgrade, Clinton said. However, NATO
officials said earlier on Saturday that an enforcement mechanism
hadn't been worked out yet.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the alliance had reaffirmed and intensified its
demands on Yugoslavia for an end to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't weakened our conditions," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
